{"title_page": "Peter Beard", "text_new": "{{other people}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Peter Beard\n| image       = PeterBeardGiraffes-HogRanch2014-wiki.jpg\n| caption     = Peter Beard at Hog Ranch in 2014 feeding giraffes\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|mf=y|1938|1|22}}\n| birth_place = New York, United States\n| nationality = American\n| occupation  = [[Artist]]\n| title       = \n| spouse      = Minnie Cushing Beard Coleman (m. 1962\u20131963)<br/>[[Cheryl Tiegs]] (m. 1982\u20131986)<br/>Nejma Khanum (m. 1986)\n| children    = 1\n| ethnicity   = \n}}\n\n'''Peter Hill Beard''' (born January 22, 1938) is an American artist, [[photographer]], [[diarist]] and writer who lives and works in [[New York City|New York City, Montauk,]] and [[Kenya]].  His photographs of [[Africa]], African animals and the journals that often integrate his photographs have been widely shown and published since the 1960s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://peterbeard.com/|title=Peter Beard Studio|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nPeter Beard was born in 1938 as a New York heir to a railroad fortune on his mother's side of the family and a tobacco inheritance on his father's.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nymag.com/news/features/peter-beard-2013-3/index1.html|title=Taming Peter Beard|website=NYMag.com|access-date=2018-01-08}}</ref> He was raised in New York City, [[Alabama]], and [[Islip, New York|Islip]], [[Long Island]], Beard began keeping diaries as a young boy and making photographs, as an extension of the diaries, at the age of 12.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=Peter Beard|date=2013|publisher=Owen, & Aronson|location=Germany|isbn=978-3-8365-3088-0|edition=Collector's}}</ref> A graduate of [[Pomfret School]], he entered [[Yale University]] in 1957, with the intention of pursuing pre-med studies, only to switch his major to [[art history]]. At Yale, he was tapped into the secret society [[Scroll and Key]]. His mentors at Yale included [[Josef Albers]], [[Richard Lindner (painter)|Richard Lindner]] and [[Vincent Scully]].\n\nInspired by earlier trips to Africa in both 1955 and 1960, Beard traveled to [[Kenya]] upon graduation. Working at [[Tsavo Conservation Area|Tsavo National Park]], he photographed and documented the demise of 35,000 [[elephant]]s and other wildlife, later to become the subject of his first book, \"The End of the Game.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=The End of the Game|date=1965|publisher=Viking Press|location=New York|isbn=978-3-8365-0530-7}}</ref>  During this time, Beard acquired Hog Ranch, a property near the [[Ngong Hills]] adjacent to the coffee farm owned by [[Karen Blixen]] (Isak Dinesen), which would become his lifelong home-base in East Africa.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=Peter Beard|date=2013|publisher=Owen, & Aronson|location=Germany|isbn=978-3-8365-3088-0|edition=Collector's}}</ref>\n\n==Art==\n\nPeter Beard's photographs of Africa, African animals and journals that often integrate his photographs have been widely shown and published since the 1970s. Each of his works is unique, a combination of his photography with elements derived from his daily diary-keeping, a practice he continues to this day. These volumes contain newspaper clippings, dried leaves, insects, old [[sepia tone|sepia]]-toned photos, transcribed telephone messages, [[marginalia]] in India ink, photographs of women, quotes, found objects, and the like; these become incorporated, with original drawings and collage by Beard. Certain of his works incorporate animal blood, sometimes Beard's own blood (in sparing quantities), a painting medium the artist favors.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Enright|first1=Robert|title=The Consummate Fragmentarian|journal=Modern Painters Magazine|date=2002}}</ref>\n\nThe Peter Beard Studio and Archive was started by Peter and Nejma Beard, and is the primary source for artwork by Peter Beard.\u00a0 The Archive maintains a repository of published and unpublished written and visual material relating to the artist\u2019s life, work, projects, travels, exhibitions, and relations with his cohort.\u00a0 www.peterbeard.com  <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://peterbeard.com/|title=Peter Beard Studio|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nBeard's first exhibition was at the Blum Helman Gallery, New York, in 1975.  Landmark museum exhibitions have been held at the [[International Center of Photography]], New York, in 1977, and the [[Centre national de la photographie]], Paris, in 1997. Gallery exhibitions followed in Berlin, London, Toronto, Madrid, Milan, Tokyo and Vienna. Beard's work is included in private collections throughout the world.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=Peter Beard|date=2013|publisher=Owen, & Aronson|location=Germany|isbn=978-3-8365-3088-0|edition=Collector's}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Beard was sued by actor [[David Spade]] who purchased one of his works. Spade tried to resell a Peter Beard photograph that he had purchased from dealer [[Peter Tunney]] but the unsigned work could not be authenticated.<ref name=artnet>{{cite news |last=Kinsella|first= Eileen|date=February 3, 2017 |title=Actor David Spade Sues Photographer Peter Beard for Failure to Authenticate a Work |url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/david-spade-sues-photographer-peter-beard-844637 |newspaper=Artnet.com|access-date=February 3, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nDescended from distinguished American families on both sides, Beard is one of three sons born to Roseanne Hoar Beard and Anson McCook Beard, Jr.  A great-grandfather, [[James Jerome Hill]], was founder of the [[Great Northern Railway (U.S.)|Great Northern Railway]] in the [[United States]] in the late 19th/early 20th centuries. Having made his fortune in the railroad business, James Jerome Hill was a great patron of the arts.  All of his heirs were exposed to and owned great collections, presumably having a strong influence on Beard\u2019s interests in the arts and beauty.\n\nBeard married his first wife (Minnie Cushing Beard Coleman) in 1967; their marriage lasted only briefly. His second wife was [[supermodel]] [[Cheryl Tiegs]], from 1982 to 1986.\n\nIn 1986, he married Nejma Khanum. The couple has a daughter, Zara, for whom his book, Zara\u2019s Tales,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=Zara's Tales: Perilous Escapades in Equatorial Africa|date=2004|publisher=Knopf|location=New York|isbn=0-679-42659-0|url=https://archive.org/details/zarastalesfromho00bear}}</ref> was written.\n\nIn 1996, he was badly injured by an elephant but survived.<ref> Alec Baldwin with Peter Beard: The Elephant Attack [https://www.americansuburbx.com/2016/01/alec-baldwin-with-peter-beard-the-elephant-attack.html www.americansuburbx.com]</ref>\n\nBeard has befriended and in some cases collaborated with many legendary artists including [[Andy Warhol]], [[Andrew Wyeth]], [[Francis Bacon (artist)|Francis Bacon]], [[Karen Blixen]], [[Truman Capote]], [[Richard Lindner (painter)|Richard Lindner]], and [[Salvador Dal\u00ed]]. He has also photographed many well-known people.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=Peter Beard|date=2013|publisher=Owen, & Aronson|location=Germany|isbn=978-3-8365-3088-0|edition=Collector's}}</ref>\n\nOn Tuesday, March 31, 2020, Peter Beard, 82, suffering from [[dementia]], wandered away from his [[Montauk, Long Island]], home off Old Montauk Highway east of Deep Hollow Ranch around 4:40 pm. Despite exhaustive searches, he was not found.<ref> Peter Beard Missing, Search Underway in Montauk [https://www.easthamptonstar.com/police-courts/202041/peter-beard-missing-search-underway-montauk]</ref> After 3 days, the case was turned over to detectives in the East Hampton Police Department.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Film !! Featured !! Director !! Producer !! Editor !! Other\n|-\n| 2017 || ''That Summer'' || Yes || No || Yes || No || No \n|-\n| 2009 || ''The Making of the 2009 Pirelli Calendar'' || Yes || No || No || No || No \n|-\n| 1994 || ''Montauk Diaries'' || Yes || No || No || No || No \n|-\n| 1988 || ''Last Word from Paradise: With Peter Beard in Africa'' || Yes || No || No || No || No \n|-\n| 1980 || ''Japanese Long Line Tuna Fishing'' || No || No || No || No || Introducer \n|-\n| 1979 || ''Africa: The End of the Game'' || Yes || No || No || No || No \n|-\n| 1976 || ''The Bicentennial Big Foot Blues'' || No || Yes || Yes || No || No \n|-\n| 1975-76 || ''Longing for Darkness'' || No || No || Yes || Yes || No \n|-\n| 1972 || ''Sisters'' (working title) || Yes || Yes || Yes || No || Initiated\n|-\n| 1963 || ''[[Hallelujah the Hills (film)|Hallelujah the Hills]]'' || Yes || No || No || No || No \n|}\n\n==Selected books==\n* Beard, Peter; Paul Theroux.  50th Anniversary Edition of The End of the Game.  Taschen.  [https://www.taschen.org ISBN]-978-3-8365-5547-0\n* Beard, Peter; Beard, Nejma; Edwards, Owen; Aronson, Steven M.L. (2008). Peter Beard (Collector\u2019s Edition). Germany: Taschen, 2006. (Art Edition) Germany: Taschen, 2007.  (Trade Edition) Germany: Taschen, 2008, 2013, and 2020. {{ISBN|978-3-8365-7742-7}}\n* Beard, Peter (1965). The End of the Game. New York: Viking Press.  Reprinted New York: Doubleday, 1977.  Japan: Camera Manichi, 1978.  Germany: Taschen, 2008.  {{ISBN|978-3-8365-0530-7}}\n* Beard, Peter (2004). Zara's Tales: Perilous Escapades in Equatorial Africa. New York: Knopf. {{ISBN|0-679-42659-0}}  \n* Beard, Peter; and Gatura, Kamante (1975). Longing for Darkness: Kamante's Tales from Out of Africa. New York: Harcourt Brace Jovanovich. {{ISBN|0-15-153080-7}}\n* Graham, Alistair, and Beard, Peter (1973). Eyelids of Morning: The Mingled Destinies of Crocodiles and Men. Greenwich, CT: New York Graphic Society. {{ISBN|0-8212-0464-5}}\n\n==Catalogues==\n\n* Beard, Peter (1999). Peter Beard: Fifty Years of Portraits. Santa Fe, NM: Arena Editions. {{ISBN|1-892041-15-4}}\n* Beard, Peter (1999). Peter Beard: Stress & Density. Vienna: KunstHausWien, Museums Betriebs Gesellschaft, mbH. {{ISBN|978-3901247071}}\n* Beard, Peter (1998). Beyond the End of the World. Milan: Universe Publishing (a division of Rizzoli International Publications, Inc.).  {{ISBN|978-0-7893-0147-5}}\n* Beard, Peter (1997). Oltre la fine del Mondo. Milan: Grafiche Milani.  \n* Beard, Peter, and Caujolle, Christian (1996). Peter Beard: Photo Poche #67. Paris: Centre national de la photographie, {{ISBN|2867541034}}\n* Beard, Peter (1993). Diary: From a Dead Man\u2019s Wallet: Confessions of a Bookmaker. Japan: Libroport Publishing Co., Ltd. {{ISBN|978-4-8457-0791-1}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* Bowermaster, Jon (1993). The adventures and misadventures of Peter Beard in Africa. Boston: [[Bulfinch Press]], 1993. {{ISBN|0-8212-1907-3}}\n* Geldzahler, Henry (1975).  Francis Bacon: Recent Paintings.  Interview with Francis Bacon by Peter Beard.  New York: [[The Metropolitan Museum of Art]].\n\n==Press==\n* Sotomayor, Karolina (Jun 20, 2016). \"'Peter Beard: Last Word From Paradise' at Guild Hall Museum\". Musee Magazine.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sotomayor|first1=Karolina|title=\"Peter Beard: Last Word From Paradise\" at Guild Hall Museum|url=http://museemagazine.com/culture/2016/6/20/peter-beard-last-word-from-paradise-at-guild-hall-museum|website=Musee Magazine}}</ref>\n* Haden-Guest, Anthony (Jun 20, 2016). \"Peter Beard Gives Us a Clear View of Paradise\". ArtNet News.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/exhibitions/peter-beard-gives-us-clear-view-paradise-517754|title=Peter Beard gives us a clear view of Paradise|last=Haden-Guest|first=Antony|date=20 June 2016|website=Artnet news|access-date=14 May 2018}}</ref>\n* Weinreich, Regina (Sep 05, 2016).\"Peter Beard: Last Word from Paradise at Guild Hall: Out of Africa\" Huffington Post.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/regina-weinreich/peter-beard-last-word-fro_b_10559212.html|title=Peter Beard: Last Word from Paradise at Guild|last1=Weinreich|first1=Regina|date=19 June 2016|website=Huffington Post|access-date=14 May 2018}}</ref>\n* Landes, Jennifer (Jun 16, 2016). \"Rare Peter Beard Show Opens\". The East Hampton Star.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Landes|first1=Jennifer|title=Rare Peter Beard Show Opens|url=http://easthamptonstar.com/Arts/2016616/Rare-Peter-Beard-Show-Opens|publisher=The East Hampton Star|date=2016-06-16}}</ref>\n* Wallace, Chris (Jun 13, 2016). \"Peter Beard\". Interview Magazine.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wallace|first1=Chris|title=Peter Beard|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/art/peter-beard/|website=Interview Magazine|publisher=Interview Magazine}}</ref>\n* After Nyne: The Art Lover's Magazine (Apr 11, 2009). \"Peter Beard: Last Word From Paradise at Guild Hall Museum, East Hampton.\u201d <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afternyne.com/single-post/2016/04/11/Peter-Beard-Last-Word-From-Paradise-at-Guild-Hall-Museum-East-Hampton|title=Peter Beard: Last Word From Paradise at Guild Hall Museum, East Hampton|website=After Nyne|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161118224033/http://www.afternyne.com/single-post/2016/04/11/Peter-Beard-Last-Word-From-Paradise-at-Guild-Hall-Museum-East-Hampton|archivedate=November 18, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* Cornet, Philippe (Aug 12, 2009).  \"Peter Beard et les annees 2000.\u201d Weekend Le Vif L'Express ([[Belgium]]).\n* (Fall/Winter 2008/09).  \"A Stunning Journey into the World of Peter Beard\", Taschen Catalogue.\n* Kulturzeit Website (Nov 12, 2008).  Buchvorstellung in Kurze: Peter Beard: Art und Collector's Edition.\n* (Jul 27, 2008)  \"Libro Peter Beard: Una aventrua africana.\u201d  [[P\u00fablico (Spain)|Publico]] (Spain).\n* Genson, Michel (Jul 6, 2008).  \"La fin d'une Afrique.\u201d  Le Republicain (Lorrain).\n* \"La Vida es un Juego Salvaje\" by Lola Huete Machado, El Pais Semanal (Spain), 1-Jun-2008\n* RandomHouse.com Dec 11, 2007.  Zara's Tales.\n* JH (Apr 2007). \"Wild at Heart.\u201d  GQ (UK). \n* Rossi, Alfredo (Feb 2007).  Il Fotografo:\"La fotografia?  E la parente povera dell'arte vera.\"  [[Corriere della Sera]] (Italy).\n* Aronson, Steven M.L. (2006).  \"A Conversation: Peter Beard on his personal history and cosmic philosophy.\"  Peter Beard, Tachen.\n* Falck, Jacaranda Caracciolo (Dec 21, 2006).  Fotografi artisti: \"Africa per sempre.\"  Espresso (Italy).\n* Roberts, Sophy (Dec 2006).  \u201cTravelista.\u201d  [[Financial Times]]: How to Spend It Magazine.\n* Edwards, Owen (Dec 2006).  \"Beard's Eye View.\"  [[Smithsonian Magazine]].\n* Abrahamsson, Carl (Dec 2006).  \"Ett Samtal Med Peter Beard: Om nagot, sa ar jap en escapist.\"  Tidningen Kulturen.\n* Gill, AA (Nov 2006).  \"Wild at Art.\"  [[The Sunday Times Magazine]].\n* Powers, Bill (Oct/Nov 2006).  \"Where the Wild Things Are.\"  Black Book.\n* Clarke, Brian (Oct 2006).  \"Wir, Dastier.\"  Vogue Deutsche.\n* Geller, Maurice (Oct 2006).  \u201cQuintessentially Legendary.\"  Quintessentially (UK).\n* Aronson, Steven (Jul 2003).  \"Out of Africa.\"  [[Architectural Digest]].\n* Enright, Robert (Autumn 2002).  \"The Consummate Fragmentarian.\"  Modern Painters Magazine. \n* Lecorn\u00e9, Isabelle-Sophie (Mar 2000).  \"Moi Peter Beard 63 Ans, Photographie, Aventurier, Provocateur.\"  Gala Magazine.\n* Rexer, Lyle (February 2, 1997). \"Defenders of a Kingdom Long Swept Aside.\" New York Times.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/02/02/arts/defenders-of-a-kingdom-long-swept-aside.html|title=Defenders of a Kingdom Long Swept Aside|last=Rexer|first=Lyle|date=2 February 1997|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 May 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.peterbeard.com Peter Beard website]\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2014}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beard, Peter}}\n[[Category:Portrait photographers]]\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American socialites]]\n[[Category:American photographers]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Pomfret School alumni]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Peter Beard\n| image       = PeterBeardGiraffes-HogRanch2014-wiki.jpg\n| caption     = Peter Beard at Hog Ranch in 2014 feeding giraffes\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|mf=y|1938|1|22}}\n| birth_place = New York, United States\n| nationality = American\n| occupation  = [[Artist]]\n| title       = \n| spouse      = Minnie Cushing Beard Coleman (m. 1962\u20131963)<br/>[[Cheryl Tiegs]] (m. 1982\u20131986)<br/>Nejma Khanum (m. 1986)\n| children    = 1\n| ethnicity   = \n}}\n\n'''Peter Hill Beard''' (born January 22, 1938) is an American artist, [[photographer]], [[diarist]] and writer who lives and works in [[New York City|New York City, Montauk,]] and [[Kenya]].  His photographs of [[Africa]], African animals and the journals that often integrate his photographs have been widely shown and published since the 1960s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://peterbeard.com/|title=Peter Beard Studio|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nPeter Beard was born in 1938 as a New York aristocrat, heir to a railroad fortune on his mother's side of the family and a tobacco inheritance on his father's.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nymag.com/news/features/peter-beard-2013-3/index1.html|title=Taming Peter Beard|website=NYMag.com|access-date=2018-01-08}}</ref> He was raised in New York City, [[Alabama]], and [[Islip, New York|Islip]], [[Long Island]], Beard began keeping diaries as a young boy and making photographs, as an extension of the diaries, at the age of 12.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=Peter Beard|date=2013|publisher=Owen, & Aronson|location=Germany|isbn=978-3-8365-3088-0|edition=Collector's}}</ref> A graduate of [[Pomfret School]], he entered [[Yale University]] in 1957, with the intention of pursuing pre-med studies, only to switch his major to [[art history]]. At Yale, he was tapped into the secret society [[Scroll and Key]]. His mentors at Yale included [[Josef Albers]], [[Richard Lindner (painter)|Richard Lindner]] and [[Vincent Scully]].\n\nInspired by earlier trips to Africa in both 1955 and 1960, Beard traveled to [[Kenya]] upon graduation. Working at [[Tsavo Conservation Area|Tsavo National Park]], he photographed and documented the demise of 35,000 [[elephant]]s and other wildlife, later to become the subject of his first book, \"The End of the Game.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=The End of the Game|date=1965|publisher=Viking Press|location=New York|isbn=978-3-8365-0530-7}}</ref>  During this time, Beard acquired Hog Ranch, a property near the [[Ngong Hills]] adjacent to the coffee farm owned by [[Karen Blixen]] (Isak Dinesen), which would become his lifelong home-base in East Africa.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=Peter Beard|date=2013|publisher=Owen, & Aronson|location=Germany|isbn=978-3-8365-3088-0|edition=Collector's}}</ref>\n\n==Art==\n\nPeter Beard's photographs of Africa, African animals and journals that often integrate his photographs have been widely shown and published since the 1970s. Each of his works is unique, a combination of his photography with elements derived from his daily diary-keeping, a practice he continues to this day. These volumes contain newspaper clippings, dried leaves, insects, old [[sepia tone|sepia]]-toned photos, transcribed telephone messages, [[marginalia]] in India ink, photographs of women, quotes, found objects, and the like; these become incorporated, with original drawings and collage by Beard. Certain of his works incorporate animal blood, sometimes Beard's own blood (in sparing quantities), a painting medium the artist favors.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Enright|first1=Robert|title=The Consummate Fragmentarian|journal=Modern Painters Magazine|date=2002}}</ref>\n\nThe Peter Beard Studio and Archive was started by Peter and Nejma Beard, and is the primary source for artwork by Peter Beard.\u00a0 The Archive maintains a repository of published and unpublished written and visual material relating to the artist\u2019s life, work, projects, travels, exhibitions, and relations with his cohort.\u00a0 www.peterbeard.com  <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://peterbeard.com/|title=Peter Beard Studio|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nBeard's first exhibition was at the Blum Helman Gallery, New York, in 1975.  Landmark museum exhibitions have been held at the [[International Center of Photography]], New York, in 1977, and the [[Centre national de la photographie]], Paris, in 1997. Gallery exhibitions followed in Berlin, London, Toronto, Madrid, Milan, Tokyo and Vienna. Beard's work is included in private collections throughout the world.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=Peter Beard|date=2013|publisher=Owen, & Aronson|location=Germany|isbn=978-3-8365-3088-0|edition=Collector's}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Beard was sued by actor [[David Spade]] who purchased one of his works. Spade tried to resell a Peter Beard photograph that he had purchased from dealer [[Peter Tunney]] but the unsigned work could not be authenticated.<ref name=artnet>{{cite news |last=Kinsella|first= Eileen|date=February 3, 2017 |title=Actor David Spade Sues Photographer Peter Beard for Failure to Authenticate a Work |url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/david-spade-sues-photographer-peter-beard-844637 |newspaper=Artnet.com|access-date=February 3, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nDescended from distinguished American families on both sides, Beard is one of three sons born to Roseanne Hoar Beard and Anson McCook Beard, Jr.  A great-grandfather, [[James Jerome Hill]], was founder of the [[Great Northern Railway (U.S.)|Great Northern Railway]] in the [[United States]] in the late 19th/early 20th centuries. Having made his fortune in the railroad business, James Jerome Hill was a great patron of the arts.  All of his heirs were exposed to and owned great collections, presumably having a strong influence on Beard\u2019s interests in the arts and beauty.\n\nBeard married his first wife (Minnie Cushing Beard Coleman) in 1967; their marriage lasted only briefly. His second wife was [[supermodel]] [[Cheryl Tiegs]], from 1982 to 1986.\n\nIn 1986, he married Nejma Khanum. The couple has a daughter, Zara, for whom his book, Zara\u2019s Tales,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=Zara's Tales: Perilous Escapades in Equatorial Africa|date=2004|publisher=Knopf|location=New York|isbn=0-679-42659-0|url=https://archive.org/details/zarastalesfromho00bear}}</ref> was written.\n\nIn 1996, he was badly injured by an elephant but survived.<ref> Alec Baldwin with Peter Beard: The Elephant Attack [https://www.americansuburbx.com/2016/01/alec-baldwin-with-peter-beard-the-elephant-attack.html www.americansuburbx.com]</ref>\n\nBeard has befriended and in some cases collaborated with many legendary artists including [[Andy Warhol]], [[Andrew Wyeth]], [[Francis Bacon (artist)|Francis Bacon]], [[Karen Blixen]], [[Truman Capote]], [[Richard Lindner (painter)|Richard Lindner]], and [[Salvador Dal\u00ed]]. He has also photographed many well-known people.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=Peter Beard|date=2013|publisher=Owen, & Aronson|location=Germany|isbn=978-3-8365-3088-0|edition=Collector's}}</ref>\n\nOn Tuesday, March 31, 2020, Peter Beard, 82, suffering from [[dementia]], wandered away from his [[Montauk, Long Island]], home off Old Montauk Highway east of Deep Hollow Ranch around 4:40 pm. Despite exhaustive searches, he was not found.<ref> Peter Beard Missing, Search Underway in Montauk [https://www.easthamptonstar.com/police-courts/202041/peter-beard-missing-search-underway-montauk]</ref> After 3 days, the case was turned over to detectives in the East Hampton Police Department.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Film !! Featured !! Director !! Producer !! Editor !! Other\n|-\n| 2017 || ''That Summer'' || Yes || No || Yes || No || No \n|-\n| 2009 || ''The Making of the 2009 Pirelli Calendar'' || Yes || No || No || No || No \n|-\n| 1994 || ''Montauk Diaries'' || Yes || No || No || No || No \n|-\n| 1988 || ''Last Word from Paradise: With Peter Beard in Africa'' || Yes || No || No || No || No \n|-\n| 1980 || ''Japanese Long Line Tuna Fishing'' || No || No || No || No || Introducer \n|-\n| 1979 || ''Africa: The End of the Game'' || Yes || No || No || No || No \n|-\n| 1976 || ''The Bicentennial Big Foot Blues'' || No || Yes || Yes || No || No \n|-\n| 1975-76 || ''Longing for Darkness'' || No || No || Yes || Yes || No \n|-\n| 1972 || ''Sisters'' (working title) || Yes || Yes || Yes || No || Initiated\n|-\n| 1963 || ''[[Hallelujah the Hills (film)|Hallelujah the Hills]]'' || Yes || No || No || No || No \n|}\n\n==Selected books==\n* Beard, Peter; Paul Theroux.  50th Anniversary Edition of The End of the Game.  Taschen.  [https://www.taschen.org ISBN]-978-3-8365-5547-0\n* Beard, Peter; Beard, Nejma; Edwards, Owen; Aronson, Steven M.L. (2008). Peter Beard (Collector\u2019s Edition). Germany: Taschen, 2006. (Art Edition) Germany: Taschen, 2007.  (Trade Edition) Germany: Taschen, 2008, 2013, and 2020. {{ISBN|978-3-8365-7742-7}}\n* Beard, Peter (1965). The End of the Game. New York: Viking Press.  Reprinted New York: Doubleday, 1977.  Japan: Camera Manichi, 1978.  Germany: Taschen, 2008.  {{ISBN|978-3-8365-0530-7}}\n* Beard, Peter (2004). Zara's Tales: Perilous Escapades in Equatorial Africa. New York: Knopf. {{ISBN|0-679-42659-0}}  \n* Beard, Peter; and Gatura, Kamante (1975). Longing for Darkness: Kamante's Tales from Out of Africa. New York: Harcourt Brace Jovanovich. {{ISBN|0-15-153080-7}}\n* Graham, Alistair, and Beard, Peter (1973). Eyelids of Morning: The Mingled Destinies of Crocodiles and Men. Greenwich, CT: New York Graphic Society. {{ISBN|0-8212-0464-5}}\n\n==Catalogues==\n\n* Beard, Peter (1999). Peter Beard: Fifty Years of Portraits. Santa Fe, NM: Arena Editions. {{ISBN|1-892041-15-4}}\n* Beard, Peter (1999). Peter Beard: Stress & Density. Vienna: KunstHausWien, Museums Betriebs Gesellschaft, mbH. {{ISBN|978-3901247071}}\n* Beard, Peter (1998). Beyond the End of the World. Milan: Universe Publishing (a division of Rizzoli International Publications, Inc.).  {{ISBN|978-0-7893-0147-5}}\n* Beard, Peter (1997). Oltre la fine del Mondo. Milan: Grafiche Milani.  \n* Beard, Peter, and Caujolle, Christian (1996). Peter Beard: Photo Poche #67. Paris: Centre national de la photographie, {{ISBN|2867541034}}\n* Beard, Peter (1993). Diary: From a Dead Man\u2019s Wallet: Confessions of a Bookmaker. Japan: Libroport Publishing Co., Ltd. {{ISBN|978-4-8457-0791-1}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* Bowermaster, Jon (1993). The adventures and misadventures of Peter Beard in Africa. Boston: [[Bulfinch Press]], 1993. {{ISBN|0-8212-1907-3}}\n* Geldzahler, Henry (1975).  Francis Bacon: Recent Paintings.  Interview with Francis Bacon by Peter Beard.  New York: [[The Metropolitan Museum of Art]].\n\n==Press==\n* Sotomayor, Karolina (Jun 20, 2016). \"'Peter Beard: Last Word From Paradise' at Guild Hall Museum\". Musee Magazine.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sotomayor|first1=Karolina|title=\"Peter Beard: Last Word From Paradise\" at Guild Hall Museum|url=http://museemagazine.com/culture/2016/6/20/peter-beard-last-word-from-paradise-at-guild-hall-museum|website=Musee Magazine}}</ref>\n* Haden-Guest, Anthony (Jun 20, 2016). \"Peter Beard Gives Us a Clear View of Paradise\". ArtNet News.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/exhibitions/peter-beard-gives-us-clear-view-paradise-517754|title=Peter Beard gives us a clear view of Paradise|last=Haden-Guest|first=Antony|date=20 June 2016|website=Artnet news|access-date=14 May 2018}}</ref>\n* Weinreich, Regina (Sep 05, 2016).\"Peter Beard: Last Word from Paradise at Guild Hall: Out of Africa\" Huffington Post.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/regina-weinreich/peter-beard-last-word-fro_b_10559212.html|title=Peter Beard: Last Word from Paradise at Guild|last1=Weinreich|first1=Regina|date=19 June 2016|website=Huffington Post|access-date=14 May 2018}}</ref>\n* Landes, Jennifer (Jun 16, 2016). \"Rare Peter Beard Show Opens\". The East Hampton Star.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Landes|first1=Jennifer|title=Rare Peter Beard Show Opens|url=http://easthamptonstar.com/Arts/2016616/Rare-Peter-Beard-Show-Opens|publisher=The East Hampton Star|date=2016-06-16}}</ref>\n* Wallace, Chris (Jun 13, 2016). \"Peter Beard\". Interview Magazine.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wallace|first1=Chris|title=Peter Beard|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/art/peter-beard/|website=Interview Magazine|publisher=Interview Magazine}}</ref>\n* After Nyne: The Art Lover's Magazine (Apr 11, 2009). \"Peter Beard: Last Word From Paradise at Guild Hall Museum, East Hampton.\u201d <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afternyne.com/single-post/2016/04/11/Peter-Beard-Last-Word-From-Paradise-at-Guild-Hall-Museum-East-Hampton|title=Peter Beard: Last Word From Paradise at Guild Hall Museum, East Hampton|website=After Nyne|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161118224033/http://www.afternyne.com/single-post/2016/04/11/Peter-Beard-Last-Word-From-Paradise-at-Guild-Hall-Museum-East-Hampton|archivedate=November 18, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* Cornet, Philippe (Aug 12, 2009).  \"Peter Beard et les annees 2000.\u201d Weekend Le Vif L'Express ([[Belgium]]).\n* (Fall/Winter 2008/09).  \"A Stunning Journey into the World of Peter Beard\", Taschen Catalogue.\n* Kulturzeit Website (Nov 12, 2008).  Buchvorstellung in Kurze: Peter Beard: Art und Collector's Edition.\n* (Jul 27, 2008)  \"Libro Peter Beard: Una aventrua africana.\u201d  [[P\u00fablico (Spain)|Publico]] (Spain).\n* Genson, Michel (Jul 6, 2008).  \"La fin d'une Afrique.\u201d  Le Republicain (Lorrain).\n* \"La Vida es un Juego Salvaje\" by Lola Huete Machado, El Pais Semanal (Spain), 1-Jun-2008\n* RandomHouse.com Dec 11, 2007.  Zara's Tales.\n* JH (Apr 2007). \"Wild at Heart.\u201d  GQ (UK). \n* Rossi, Alfredo (Feb 2007).  Il Fotografo:\"La fotografia?  E la parente povera dell'arte vera.\"  [[Corriere della Sera]] (Italy).\n* Aronson, Steven M.L. (2006).  \"A Conversation: Peter Beard on his personal history and cosmic philosophy.\"  Peter Beard, Tachen.\n* Falck, Jacaranda Caracciolo (Dec 21, 2006).  Fotografi artisti: \"Africa per sempre.\"  Espresso (Italy).\n* Roberts, Sophy (Dec 2006).  \u201cTravelista.\u201d  [[Financial Times]]: How to Spend It Magazine.\n* Edwards, Owen (Dec 2006).  \"Beard's Eye View.\"  [[Smithsonian Magazine]].\n* Abrahamsson, Carl (Dec 2006).  \"Ett Samtal Med Peter Beard: Om nagot, sa ar jap en escapist.\"  Tidningen Kulturen.\n* Gill, AA (Nov 2006).  \"Wild at Art.\"  [[The Sunday Times Magazine]].\n* Powers, Bill (Oct/Nov 2006).  \"Where the Wild Things Are.\"  Black Book.\n* Clarke, Brian (Oct 2006).  \"Wir, Dastier.\"  Vogue Deutsche.\n* Geller, Maurice (Oct 2006).  \u201cQuintessentially Legendary.\"  Quintessentially (UK).\n* Aronson, Steven (Jul 2003).  \"Out of Africa.\"  [[Architectural Digest]].\n* Enright, Robert (Autumn 2002).  \"The Consummate Fragmentarian.\"  Modern Painters Magazine. \n* Lecorn\u00e9, Isabelle-Sophie (Mar 2000).  \"Moi Peter Beard 63 Ans, Photographie, Aventurier, Provocateur.\"  Gala Magazine.\n* Rexer, Lyle (February 2, 1997). \"Defenders of a Kingdom Long Swept Aside.\" New York Times.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/02/02/arts/defenders-of-a-kingdom-long-swept-aside.html|title=Defenders of a Kingdom Long Swept Aside|last=Rexer|first=Lyle|date=2 February 1997|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 May 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.peterbeard.com Peter Beard website]\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2014}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beard, Peter}}\n[[Category:Portrait photographers]]\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American socialites]]\n[[Category:American photographers]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Pomfret School alumni]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Vleigh098", "label": "safe", "comment": "not an aristocrat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Beard"}
{"title_page": "Joe Cronin", "text_new": "{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Joe Cronin\n|image=Joe Cronin 1937 cropped.jpg\n|caption = Cronin with the Boston Red Sox in 1937\n|position=[[Shortstop]] / [[Manager (baseball)|Manager]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1906|10|12}}\n|birth_place=[[San Francisco, California]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|1984|9|7|1906|10|12}}\n|death_place=[[Osterville, Massachusetts]]\n|bats=Right\n|throws=Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=April 29\n|debutyear=1926\n|debutteam=Pittsburgh Pirates\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=April 19\n|finalyear=1945\n|finalteam=Boston Red Sox\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value=.301\n|stat2label=[[Hit (baseball)|Hits]]\n|stat2value=2,285\n|stat3label=[[Home run]]s\n|stat3value=170\n|stat4label=[[Runs batted in]]\n|stat4value=1,424\n|stat5label=Managerial record\n|stat5value=1,236\u20131,055\n|stat6label=Winning %\n|stat6value={{winning percentage|1236|1055}}\n|teams=\n'''As player'''\n* [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] ({{mlby|1926}}\u2013{{mlby|1927}})\n* [[Washington Senators (1901\u201360)|Washington Senators]] ({{mlby|1928}}\u2013{{mlby|1934}})\n* [[Boston Red Sox]] ({{mlby|1935}}\u2013{{mlby|1945}})\n'''As manager'''\n* [[Washington Senators (1901\u201360)|Washington Senators]] ({{mlby|1933}}\u2013{{mlby|1934}})\n* [[Boston Red Sox]] ({{mlby|1935}}\u2013{{mlby|1947}})\n|highlights=\n*7\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[1933 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1933]]\u2013[[1935 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1935]], [[1937 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1937]]\u2013[[1939 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1939]], [[1941 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1941]])\n*[[Boston Red Sox#Retired numbers|Boston Red Sox No. 4]] retired\n* [[Boston Red Sox Hall of Fame]]\n* [[Washington Nationals#Ring of Honor|Washington Nationals Ring of Honor]] \n|hoflink = National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum\n|hoftype = National\n|hofdate=[[1956 Baseball Hall of Fame balloting|1956]]\n|hofvote=78.76% (tenth ballot)\n}}\n\n'''Joseph Edward Cronin''' (October 12, 1906 \u2013 September 7, 1984) was a [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) [[shortstop]], [[Manager (baseball)|manager]] and general manager. He spent over 48 years in baseball, culminating with 14 years as president of the [[American League]] (AL).\n\nDuring his 20-year playing career (1926\u20131945), Cronin played for three teams, primarily the [[Boston Red Sox]]; he was a [[Player-coach|player-manager]] for 13 seasons (1933\u20131945), and served as manager for two additional seasons (1946\u20131947). A seven-time [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]], Cronin became the first AL player to become an All-Star with two teams; he was elected to the [[Baseball Hall of Fame]] in [[1956 Baseball Hall of Fame balloting|1956]].\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:1937 all stars crop FINAL2.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Seven of the American League's 1937 All-Star players, from left to right [[Lou Gehrig]], Joe Cronin, [[Bill Dickey]], [[Joe DiMaggio]], [[Charlie Gehringer]], [[Jimmie Foxx]], and [[Hank Greenberg]]. All seven were eventually elected to the Baseball Hall of Fame.]]\nCronin was born in Excelsior District of [[San Francisco, California]]. The [[1906 San Francisco earthquake]] had cost his Irish Catholic parents almost all of their possessions.<ref name=Corcoran>{{cite book|last=Corcoran|first=Dennis|title=Induction Day at Cooperstown: A History of the Baseball Hall of Fame Ceremony|year=2010|publisher=McFarland|isbn=0786444169|page=68|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3dF2PsAeDeYC&pg=PA68&dq=joe+cronin+death&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ZuFxUsatC-visAT454CYBA&ved=0CF8Q6AEwBg#v=onepage}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Armour|first1=Mark|title=Joe Cronin|url=http://sabr.org/bioproj/person/572b61e8|website=Society for American Baseball Research|accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref> Cronin attended Sacred Heart High School. He played several sports as a child and he won a city tennis championship for his age group when he was 14. As he was not greatly interested in school, Cronin's grades improved only when the [[San Francisco Seals (baseball)|San Francisco Seals]] of the [[Pacific Coast League]] began giving away tickets to students with good conduct and attendance. At the time, the nearest MLB team was nearly 2,000 miles from San Francisco.<ref>Armour, pp. 9-10.</ref>\n\n==Major league career==\n\n===As a player===\nBaseball promoter [[Joe Engel]], who scouted for the Senators and managed the [[Chattanooga Lookouts]] at [[Engel Stadium]], originally signed Cronin. Engel first spotted Cronin playing in [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]]. \"I knew I was watching a great player\", Engel said. \"I bought Cronin at a time he was hitting .221. When I told [[Clark Griffith]] what I had done, he screamed, 'You paid $7,500 for that bum? Well, you didn't buy him for me. You bought him for yourself. He's not my ballplayer \u2013 he's yours. You keep him and don't either you or Cronin show up at the ballpark.'\"<ref name=Emerald>{{cite book|last=Rosen|first=Charley|title=The Emerald Diamond: How the Irish Transformed America's Favorite Pastime|year=2012|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|isbn=0062089919|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SI7M0GwFsWEC&pg=PT239&dq=cronin+griffith+bought+him+for+yourself&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ld9xUuzaEMaisASqkoHIDA&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=cronin%20griffith%20bought%20him%20for%20yourself&f=false}}</ref>\n\nIn {{mlby|1930}}, Cronin had a breakout year, batting .346 with 13 [[home run]]s and 126 [[runs batted in|RBI]]. Cronin won both the AL Writers' MVP (the forerunner of the BBWAA MVP, established in 1931) and the [[The Sporting News Most Valuable Player Award|AL Sporting News MVP]]. His 1931 season was also outstanding, with him posting a .306 [[batting average (baseball)|average]], 12 home runs, and 126 RBIs. Cronin led the Senators to the [[1933 World Series]] and later married Griffith's niece, Mildred Robertson.\n\n===As a player-manager and manager===\nCronin was named player-manager of the Senators in {{mlby|1933}}, a post he would hold for two years. In his first year, he led the Senators to what would be their last pennant in Washington. \n\nWhile Cronin was on his honeymoon with Mildred in his hometown of San Francisco, he got a message from Griffith\u2013the [[Boston Red Sox]] had offered the Senators their starting shortstop, [[Lyn Lary]], in return for Cronin and $250,000. Red Sox owner [[Tom Yawkey]] also offered Cronin a five-year contract as player-manager. Well aware of the Senators' perennial financial problems (Griffith had no income apart from the Senators), Cronin accepted the trade.<ref name=SABR>{{cite web|url=https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/572b61e8|title=Joe Cronin|author1=Mark Armour|publisher=[[Society for American Baseball Research]]|date=2015}}</ref> Cronin remained as player-manager of the Red Sox until {{mlby|1945}}, then remained solely as manager until {{mlby|1947}}.\n\nAs early as {{mlby|1938}}, it was apparent that Cronin was nearing the end of his playing career. Red Sox farm director [[Billy Evans]] thought he had found Cronin's successor in [[Pee Wee Reese]], the star shortstop for the [[Louisville Colonels (minor league baseball)|Louisville Colonels]] of the Triple-A [[American Association (20th century)|American Association]]. He was so impressed by Reese that he was able to talk Yawkey into buying the Colonels and making them the Red Sox' top farm club. However, when Yawkey and Evans asked Cronin to scout Reese, Cronin realized he was scouting his replacement. Believing that he was still had enough left to be a regular player, Cronin deliberately downplayed Reese's talent and suggested that the Red Sox trade him. Reese was eventually traded to the [[Brooklyn Dodgers]], where he went on to a Hall of Fame career.<ref name=Neyer>{{cite book |last=Neyer |first=Rob |authorlink=Rob Neyer |coauthors= |title=Rob Neyer's Big Book of Baseball Blunders |year=2006 |publisher=Fireside |location=New York City |isbn=0-7432-8491-7 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/robneyersbigbook0000neye }}</ref> As it turned out, Evans' and Yawkey's initial concerns about Cronin were valid. His last year as a full-time player was {{mlby|1941}}; after that year, he never played more than 76 games per season. \n\nEven when [[World War II]] saw dozens of young players either enlist or be drafted, Cronin limited his playing appearances to cameo roles as a utility infielder and pinch-hitter.<ref name=SABR/>  On June 17, 1943, Cronin sent himself into pinch hit in both games of a doubleheader and hit a home run each time. \n\nIn April 1945, he broke his leg in a game against the Yankees. He sat out the remainder of the season, and retired as a player for good at the end of the year.<ref name=SABR/>\n\nOver his career, Cronin batted .300 or higher eight times, as well as driving in 100 runs or more eight times. He finished with a .301 average, 170 home runs, and 1,424 RBIs.\n\nAs a manager, he compiled a 1,236\u20131,055 record and won two [[American League]] pennants (in 1933 and 1946). His 1933 Senators dropped the [[1933 World Series]] to the [[New York Giants (NL)|New York Giants]], and his 1946 Red Sox lost the [[1946 World Series]] to the [[St. Louis Cardinals]].\n\n===As a general manager===\nAt the end of the 1947 season, Cronin succeeded [[Eddie Collins]] as [[general manager]] of the Red Sox and held the post for over 11 years, through mid-January {{mlby|1959}}. The Red Sox challenged for the AL pennant in {{mlby|1948}}\u2013[[1949 in baseball|49]] (finishing second by a single game both seasons) thanks to Cronin's aggressive trades. In his first off-season, he acquired shortstop [[Vern Stephens]] and [[pitcher]]s [[Ellis Kinder]] and [[Jack Kramer (baseball)|Jack Kramer]] from the [[St. Louis Browns]]; all played major roles in Boston's [[1948 Boston Red Sox season|1948 season]], when the Red Sox finished in a flatfooted tie for the pennant but lost a [[1948 American League tie-breaker game|one-game tie-breaker]]. Kinder and Stephens were centerpieces of the Red Sox' 1949\u201350 contenders as well. In the former year, they were edged out by the Yankees during the regular season's final weekend; in the latter, they finished third but came within three games of the league-leading Yanks.\n\nAs it turned out, {{mlby|1950}} was the last hurrah for the Red Sox during Cronin's tenure as general manager. With the exception of [[Ted Williams]] (who missed most of the 1952\u201353 seasons while serving in the [[Korean War]]), the core of the 1946\u201350 team aged quickly and the Red Sox faced a significant rebuilding job starting in {{mlby|1952}}. Cronin's acquisition of future [[American League Most Valuable Player]] [[Jackie Jensen]] from Washington in {{mlby|1954}} represented a coup, but the club misfired on several [[bonus baby|\"bonus babies\"]] who never lived up to their potential. The Red Sox posted winning season records for all but two of Cronin's 11 seasons as general manager, but from 1951\u201358 they lagged behind the AL pennant-winners by an average of 17<small>{{fraction|3|4}}</small> games. Then, beginning in {{mlby|1959}}, they began a skein of eight straight below-.500 and second-division campaigns. They would not be a factor in a pennant race again until the \"Impossible Dream\" season of 1967.\n\nMost attention has been focused on Cronin and Yawkey's refusal to [[Baseball color line|integrate]] the Red Sox roster; by January 1959, when Cronin's tenure as general manager ended, the Red Sox were the only team in the big leagues without an [[African-American]] or [[Afro-Latin Americans|Afro-Latin American]] player.  Notably, Cronin once passed on signing a young [[Willie Mays]] and never traded for an African-American player.<ref name=\"edes\">[http://espn.go.com/blog/boston/red-sox/post/_/id/36622/george-digby-and-willie-mays-the-one-who-got-away Edes, Gordon, ''George Digby and Willie Mays: The One Who Got Away.'' [[ESPN|ESPN Boston]], May 3, 2014]</ref> The Red Sox did not break the [[baseball color line]] until six months after Cronin's departure for the AL presidency, when they promoted [[Pumpsie Green]], a [[utility (baseball)|utility]] [[infielder]], from their [[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]] affiliate, the [[Minneapolis Millers]], in July 1959.\n\n===As AL president===\nIn January 1959, Cronin was elected president of the American League, the first former player to be so elected and the fourth full-time chief executive in the league's history. When he replaced the retiring [[Will Harridge]], who became board chairman, Cronin moved the league's headquarters from [[Chicago]] to [[Boston]]. Cronin served as AL president until December 31, 1973, when he was succeeded by [[Lee MacPhail]].\n\nDuring Cronin's 15 years in office, the Junior Circuit [[expansion team|expanded]] from eight to 12 teams, adding the [[Los Angeles Angels]] and [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|expansion Washington Senators]] in {{mlby|1961}}<ref>[https://sabr.org/research/mis-management-101-american-league-expansion-1961 McCue, Andy, and Thompson, Eric (2011), \"Mismanagement 101: The American League's Expansion of 1961.\" ''The National Pastime 2011,'' [[Society for American Baseball Research]]]</ref>  and the [[Kansas City Royals]] and [[Seattle Pilots]] in {{mlby|1969}}.\n\nIt also endured four franchise shifts: the relocation of the original Senators club (owned by Cronin's brother-in-law and sister-in-law, [[Calvin Griffith]] and [[Thelma Griffith Haynes]]) to [[Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul]], creating the [[Minnesota Twins]] (1961); the shift of the [[Oakland Athletics|Athletics]] from [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]] to [[Oakland, California|Oakland]] ({{mlby|1968}}); the transfer of the Pilots after only one season in [[Seattle]] to [[Milwaukee]] as the [[Milwaukee Brewers|Brewers]] ({{mlby|1970}}); and the transplantation of the expansion Senators after 11 seasons in Washington, D.C., to [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth]] as the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] ({{mlby|1972}}). The Angels also moved from Los Angeles to adjacent [[Orange County, California|Orange County]] in {{mlby|1966}} and adopted a regional identity, in part because of the dominance of the [[National League]] [[Los Angeles Dodgers|Dodgers]], who were the Angels' landlords at [[Dodger Stadium|\"Chavez Ravine\" (Dodger Stadium)]] from 1962\u201365.  Of the four expansion teams that joined the league beginning in 1961, three abandoned their original host cities within a dozen years (the Pilots after only one season), and only one team\u2014the Royals\u2014remained in its original municipality. Two of the charter members of the old eight-team league, the [[Chicago White Sox]] and [[Cleveland Indians]], also suffered significant attendance woes and were targets of relocation efforts by other cities.\n\nIn addition, the AL found itself at a competitive disadvantage compared with the National League during Cronin's term. With strong teams in larger markets and a host of new stadiums, the NL outdrew the AL for 33 consecutive years (1956\u201388).<ref name=\"joeblows\">{{cite book|last1=Studenmund|first1=Dave|last2=Tamer|first2=Greg|title=The Hardball Times 2004 Baseball Annual|year=2004|publisher=The Hardball Times|isbn=|page=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0ry_K7X-iKIC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> In 1973, Cronin's final season as league president, the NL attracted 55 percent of total MLB attendance, 16.62 million vs. 13.38 million total fans, despite the opening of [[Royals Stadium]] in Kansas City and the American League's adoption of the [[designated hitter]] rule, which was designed to spark scoring and fan interest. While the National League held only an 8\u20137 edge in [[World Series]] play during the Cronin era, it dominated the [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game]], going 15\u20133\u20131 in the 19 games played from 1959\u201373.\n\nAfter the {{by|1968}} season, Cronin drew headlines when he fired AL [[umpire (baseball)|umpires]] [[Al Salerno]] and [[Bill Valentine]], ostensibly for poor performance; however, it later surfaced that the two officials were fired for attempting to organize an umpires' [[trade union|union]]. Neither man was reinstated (Valentine became a successful [[minor league baseball|minor league]] front-office executive), but the [[Major League Umpires Association]] was formed anyway, two years later.<ref>{{cite news|first=Mark|last=Armour|title=A Tale of Two Umpires: When Al Salerno and Bill Valentine Were Thrown Out of the Game|url=http://sabr.org/research/tale-two-umpires-when-al-salerno-and-bill-valentine-got-thrown-out-game|accessdate=July 14, 2017|agency=[[Society for American Baseball Research]]|publisher=sabr.org|date=2009}}</ref> However, in 1966, Cronin was hailed for [[racial integration|integrating]] MLB's umpiring staff with the promotion of veteran minor league arbiter [[Emmett Ashford]] to the American League.<ref>{{cite news|first=Mark|last=Armour|title=Emmett Ashford|url=https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/40af3222|accessdate=July 14, 2017|agency=[[Society for American Baseball Research]]|publisher=sabr.org|date=2007}}</ref>\n\n{{MLBBioRet\n|Image  = Red sox retired 4.png\n|Name   = Joe Cronin\n|Number = 4\n|Team   = Boston Red Sox\n|Year   = 1984\n|}}\n\n===Hall of Fame===\nJoe Cronin was inducted into the [[Baseball Hall of Fame]] (with [[Hank Greenberg]]) in 1956.\n\n==Career Statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! [[Games played|G]] !! [[At bat|AB]] !! [[Run (baseball)|R]] !! [[Hit (baseball)|H]] !! [[Double (baseball)|2B]] !! [[Triple (baseball)|3B]] !! [[Home run|HR]] !! [[Runs batted in|RBI]] !! [[Base on balls|BB]] !! [[Batting average (baseball)|AVG]] !! [[On-base percentage|OBP]] !! [[Slugging percentage|SLG]] !! [[Fielding percentage|FLD%]]\n|-\n| 2,124 || 7,579 || 1,233 || 2,285 || 515 || 118 || 170 || 1,424 || 1,059 || .301 || .390 || .468 || .953\n|}\n\n==Death==\nIn the last months of his life, Cronin struggled with cancer that had invaded his prostate and bones; he suffered a great deal of bone pain as a result.<ref>Armour, p. 330.</ref> Cronin came to [[Fenway Park]] for one of his last public appearances when his jersey number 4 was retired by the Red Sox on May 29, 1984. He died at the age of 77 on September 7, 1984, at his home in [[Osterville, Massachusetts]].<ref name=Morning>{{cite news|title=Joe Cronin, baseball legend, American League president|url=http://articles.mcall.com/1984-09-08/news/2428646_1_first-al-pennant-joe-cronin-great-man|accessdate=November 29, 2014|work=[[The Morning Call]]|date=September 8, 1984}}</ref> He is buried in St. Francis Xavier Cemetery in nearby Centerville.\n\n==Legacy==\nAt the number retirement ceremony shortly before Cronin's death, teammate [[Ted Williams]] commented on how much he respected Cronin as a father and a man. Cronin was also remembered as a [[clutch hitter]]. Manager [[Connie Mack]] once commented, \"With a man on third and one out, I'd rather have Cronin hitting for me than anybody I've ever seen, and that includes Cobb, Simmons and the rest of them.\"<ref name=NYT>{{cite news|title=Joe Cronin, an ex-executive and star player in baseball|url=http://www.thedeadballera.com/Obits/Obits_C/Cronin.Joe.Obit.html|accessdate=November 29, 2014|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 8, 1984}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, he was named to the [[Major League Baseball All-Century Team]].<ref name=ACT>{{cite web|title=The All-Century Team|url=http://www.mlb.com/mlb/history/mlb_history_moreinfo.jsp|publisher=[[MLB.com]]|accessdate=October 31, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Baseball}}\n* [[Boston Red Sox Hall of Fame]]\n* [[Bay Area Sports Hall of Fame]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career hits leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career doubles leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career triples leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career runs scored leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career runs batted in leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball annual doubles leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball annual triples leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball players to hit for the cycle]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball player-managers]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball managers by wins]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*Armour, Mark (2010). [https://books.google.com/books?id=nGZ9CyVWkmQC ''Joe Cronin: A Life in Baseball'']. [[University of Nebraska Press]]. {{ISBN|0803229968}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n{{bbhof|cronin-joe}}\n{{Baseballstats|mlb=|espn=|br=c/cronijo01|fangraphs=1002796|retro=C/Pcronj101}}\n{{Baseball-reference manager|cronijo01}}\n*{{findagrave}}\n^[https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/572b61e8 Joe Cronin] at SABR (Baseball BioProject)\n:<br>\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-ach|ach}}\n{{Succession box| before = [[Ski Melillo]]<br>[[Buddy Rosar]] | title = [[Hitting for the cycle]]| years = September 2, 1929<br>August 2, 1940 | after = [[Freddie Lindstrom]]<br>[[Joe Gordon]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{1956 Baseball HOF}}\n{{Baseball Hall of Fame members}}\n{{AL Presidents}}\n{{TwinsManagers}}\n{{Boston Red Sox retired numbers}}\n{{Boston Red Sox managers}}\n{{Boston Red Sox general managers}}\n{{Boston Red Sox Hall of Fame}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cronin, Joe}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1984 deaths]]\n[[Category:American League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:American League presidents]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from California]]\n[[Category:Boston Red Sox executives]]\n[[Category:Boston Red Sox managers]]\n[[Category:Boston Red Sox players]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Johnstown Johnnies players]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Blues (baseball) players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball general managers]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball player-managers]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball players with retired numbers]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball shortstops]]\n[[Category:National Baseball Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:New Haven Profs players]]\n[[Category:People from Osterville, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Pirates players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Washington Senators (1901\u201360) managers]]\n[[Category:Washington Senators (1901\u201360) players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Joe Cronin\n|image=Joe Cronin 1937 cropped.jpg\n|image_size = \n|caption = Cronin with the Boston Red Sox in 1937\n|position=[[Shortstop]] / [[Manager (baseball)|Manager]]\n|birth_date={{birth date|1906|10|12}}\n|birth_place=[[San Francisco, California]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|1984|9|7|1906|10|12}}\n|death_place=[[Osterville, Massachusetts]]\n|bats=Right\n|throws=Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=April 29\n|debutyear=1926\n|debutteam=Pittsburgh Pirates\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=April 19\n|finalyear=1945\n|finalteam=Boston Red Sox\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value=.301\n|stat2label=[[Hit (baseball)|Hits]]\n|stat2value=2,285\n|stat3label=[[Home run]]s\n|stat3value=170\n|stat4label=[[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n|stat4value=1,424\n|stat5label=Managerial record\n|stat5value=1,236\u20131,055\n|stat6label=Winning %\n|stat6value={{winning percentage|1236|1055}}\n|teams=\n'''As player'''\n* [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] ({{mlby|1926}}\u2013{{mlby|1927}})\n* [[Washington Senators (1901\u201360)|Washington Senators]] ({{mlby|1928}}\u2013{{mlby|1934}})\n* [[Boston Red Sox]] ({{mlby|1935}}\u2013{{mlby|1945}})\n'''As manager'''\n* [[Washington Senators (1901\u201360)|Washington Senators]] ({{mlby|1933}}\u2013{{mlby|1934}})\n* [[Boston Red Sox]] ({{mlby|1935}}\u2013{{mlby|1947}})\n|highlights=\n*7\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[1933 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1933]]\u2013[[1935 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1935]], [[1937 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1937]]\u2013[[1939 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1939]], [[1941 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1941]])\n*[[Boston Red Sox#Retired numbers|Boston Red Sox No. 4]] retired\n* [[Boston Red Sox Hall of Fame]]\n* [[Washington Nationals#Ring of Honor|Washington Nationals Ring of Honor]] \n|hoflink = National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum\n|hoftype = National\n|hofdate=[[1956 Baseball Hall of Fame balloting|1956]]\n|hofvote=78.76% (tenth ballot)\n}}\n\n'''Joseph Edward Cronin''' (October 12, 1906 \u2013 September 7, 1984) was a [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) [[shortstop]], [[Manager (baseball)|manager]] and general manager. He spent over 48 years in baseball, culminating with 14 years as president of the [[American League]] (AL).\n\nDuring his 20-year playing career (1926\u20131945), Cronin played for three teams, primarily the [[Boston Red Sox]]; he was a [[Player-coach|player-manager]] for 13 seasons (1933\u20131945), and served as manager for two additional seasons (1946\u20131947). A seven-time [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]], Cronin became the first AL player to become an All-Star with two teams; he was elected to the [[Baseball Hall of Fame]] in [[1956 Baseball Hall of Fame balloting|1956]].\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:1937 all stars crop FINAL2.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Seven of the American League's 1937 All-Star players, from left to right [[Lou Gehrig]], Joe Cronin, [[Bill Dickey]], [[Joe DiMaggio]], [[Charlie Gehringer]], [[Jimmie Foxx]], and [[Hank Greenberg]]. All seven were eventually elected to the Baseball Hall of Fame.]]\nCronin was born in Excelsior District of [[San Francisco, California]]. The [[1906 San Francisco earthquake]] had cost his Irish Catholic parents almost all of their possessions.<ref name=Corcoran>{{cite book|last=Corcoran|first=Dennis|title=Induction Day at Cooperstown: A History of the Baseball Hall of Fame Ceremony|year=2010|publisher=McFarland|isbn=0786444169|page=68|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3dF2PsAeDeYC&pg=PA68&dq=joe+cronin+death&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ZuFxUsatC-visAT454CYBA&ved=0CF8Q6AEwBg#v=onepage}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Armour|first1=Mark|title=Joe Cronin|url=http://sabr.org/bioproj/person/572b61e8|website=Society for American Baseball Research|accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref> Cronin attended Sacred Heart High School. He played several sports as a child and he won a city tennis championship for his age group when he was 14. As he was not greatly interested in school, Cronin's grades improved only when the [[San Francisco Seals (baseball)|San Francisco Seals]] of the [[Pacific Coast League]] began giving away tickets to students with good conduct and attendance. At the time, the nearest MLB team was nearly 2,000 miles from San Francisco.<ref>Armour, pp. 9-10.</ref>\n\n==Major league career==\n\n===As a player===\nBaseball promoter [[Joe Engel]], who scouted for the Senators and managed the [[Chattanooga Lookouts]] at [[Engel Stadium]], originally signed Cronin. Engel first spotted Cronin playing in [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]]. \"I knew I was watching a great player\", Engel said. \"I bought Cronin at a time he was hitting .221. When I told [[Clark Griffith]] what I had done, he screamed, 'You paid $7,500 for that bum? Well, you didn't buy him for me. You bought him for yourself. He's not my ballplayer \u2013 he's yours. You keep him and don't either you or Cronin show up at the ballpark.'\"<ref name=Emerald>{{cite book|last=Rosen|first=Charley|title=The Emerald Diamond: How the Irish Transformed America's Favorite Pastime|year=2012|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|isbn=0062089919|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SI7M0GwFsWEC&pg=PT239&dq=cronin+griffith+bought+him+for+yourself&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ld9xUuzaEMaisASqkoHIDA&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=cronin%20griffith%20bought%20him%20for%20yourself&f=false}}</ref>\n\nIn {{Baseball year|1930}}, Cronin had a breakout year, batting .346 with 13 [[home run]]s and 126 [[runs batted in|RBI]]. Cronin won both the AL Writers' MVP (the forerunner of the BBWAA MVP, established in 1931) and the [[The Sporting News Most Valuable Player Award|AL Sporting News MVP]]. His 1931 season was also outstanding, with him posting a .306 [[batting average (baseball)|average]], 12 home runs, and 126 RBIs. Cronin led the Senators to the [[1933 World Series]] and later married Griffith's niece, Mildred Robertson.\n\n===As a player-manager and manager===\nCronin was named player-manager of the Senators in {{Baseball year|1933}}, a post he would hold for two years. In his first year, he led the Senators to what would be their last pennant in Washington. \n\nWhile Cronin was on his honeymoon with Mildred in his hometown of San Francisco, he got a message from Griffith\u2013the [[Boston Red Sox]] had offered the Senators their starting shortstop, [[Lyn Lary]], in return for Cronin and $250,000. Red Sox owner [[Tom Yawkey]] also offered Cronin a five-year contract as player-manager. Well aware of the Senators' perennial financial problems (Griffith had no income apart from the Senators), Cronin accepted the trade.<ref name=SABR>{{cite web|url=https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/572b61e8|title=Joe Cronin|author1=Mark Armour|publisher=[[Society for American Baseball Research]]|date=2015}}</ref> Cronin remained as player-manager of the Red Sox until {{Baseball year|1945}}, then remained solely as manager until {{Baseball year|1947}}.\n\nAs early as {{baseball year|1938}}, it was apparent that Cronin was nearing the end of his playing career. Red Sox farm director [[Billy Evans]] thought he had found Cronin's successor in [[Pee Wee Reese]], the star shortstop for the [[Louisville Colonels (minor league baseball)|Louisville Colonels]] of the Triple-A [[American Association (20th century)|American Association]]. He was so impressed by Reese that he was able to talk Yawkey into buying the Colonels and making them the Red Sox' top farm club. However, when Yawkey and Evans asked Cronin to scout Reese, Cronin realized he was scouting his replacement. Believing that he was still had enough left to be a regular player, Cronin deliberately downplayed Reese's talent and suggested that the Red Sox trade him. Reese was eventually traded to the [[Brooklyn Dodgers]], where he went on to a Hall of Fame career.<ref name=Neyer>{{cite book |last=Neyer |first=Rob |authorlink=Rob Neyer |coauthors= |title=Rob Neyer's Big Book of Baseball Blunders |year=2006 |publisher=Fireside |location=New York City |isbn=0-7432-8491-7 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/robneyersbigbook0000neye }}</ref> As it turned out, Evans' and Yawkey's initial concerns about Cronin were valid. His last year as a full-time player was {{baseball year|1941}}; after that year, he never played more than 76 games per season. \n\nEven when [[World War II]] saw dozens of young players either enlist or be drafted, Cronin limited his playing appearances to cameo roles as a utility infielder and pinch-hitter.<ref name=SABR/>  On June 17, 1943, Cronin sent himself into pinch hit in both games of a doubleheader and hit a home run each time. \n\nIn April 1945, he broke his leg in a game against the Yankees. He sat out the remainder of the season, and retired as a player for good at the end of the year.<ref name=SABR/>\n\nOver his career, Cronin batted .300 or higher eight times, as well as driving in 100 runs or more eight times. He finished with a .301 average, 170 home runs, and 1,424 RBIs.\n\nAs a manager, he compiled a 1,236\u20131,055 record and won two [[American League]] pennants (in 1933 and 1946). His 1933 Senators dropped the [[1933 World Series]] to the [[New York Giants (NL)|New York Giants]], and his 1946 Red Sox lost the [[1946 World Series]] to the [[St. Louis Cardinals]].\n\n===As a general manager===\nAt the end of the 1947 season, Cronin succeeded [[Eddie Collins]] as [[general manager]] of the Red Sox and held the post for over 11 years, through mid-January {{Baseball year|1959}}. The Red Sox challenged for the AL pennant in {{Baseball year|1948}}\u2013[[1949 in baseball|49]] (finishing second by a single game both seasons) thanks to Cronin's aggressive trades. In his first off-season, he acquired shortstop [[Vern Stephens]] and [[pitcher]]s [[Ellis Kinder]] and [[Jack Kramer (baseball)|Jack Kramer]] from the [[St. Louis Browns]]; all played major roles in Boston's [[1948 Boston Red Sox season|1948 season]], when the Red Sox finished in a flatfooted tie for the pennant but lost a [[1948 American League tie-breaker game|one-game tie-breaker]]. Kinder and Stephens were centerpieces of the Red Sox' 1949\u201350 contenders as well. In the former year, they were edged out by the Yankees during the regular season's final weekend; in the latter, they finished third but came within three games of the league-leading Yanks.\n\nAs it turned out, {{baseball year|1950}} was the last hurrah for the Red Sox during Cronin's tenure as general manager. With the exception of [[Ted Williams]] (who missed most of the 1952\u201353 seasons while serving in the [[Korean War]]), the core of the 1946\u201350 team aged quickly and the Red Sox faced a significant rebuilding job starting in {{baseball year|1952}}. Cronin's acquisition of future [[American League Most Valuable Player]] [[Jackie Jensen]] from Washington in {{baseball year|1954}} represented a coup, but the club misfired on several [[bonus baby|\"bonus babies\"]] who never lived up to their potential. The Red Sox posted winning season records for all but two of Cronin's 11 seasons as general manager, but from 1951\u201358 they lagged behind the AL pennant-winners by an average of 17<small>{{fraction|3|4}}</small> games. Then, beginning in {{mlby|1959}}, they began a skein of eight straight below-.500 and second-division campaigns. They would not be a factor in a pennant race again until the \"Impossible Dream\" season of 1967.\n\nMost attention has been focused on Cronin and Yawkey's refusal to [[Baseball color line|integrate]] the Red Sox roster; by January 1959, when Cronin's tenure as general manager ended, the Red Sox were the only team in the big leagues without an [[African-American]] or [[Afro-Latin Americans|Afro-Latin American]] player.  Notably, Cronin once passed on signing a young [[Willie Mays]] and never traded for an African-American player.<ref name=\"edes\">[http://espn.go.com/blog/boston/red-sox/post/_/id/36622/george-digby-and-willie-mays-the-one-who-got-away Edes, Gordon, ''George Digby and Willie Mays: The One Who Got Away.'' [[ESPN|ESPN Boston]], May 3, 2014]</ref> The Red Sox did not break the [[baseball color line]] until six months after Cronin's departure for the AL presidency, when they promoted [[Pumpsie Green]], a [[utility (baseball)|utility]] [[infielder]], from their [[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]] affiliate, the [[Minneapolis Millers]], in July 1959.\n\n===As AL president===\nIn January 1959, Cronin was elected president of the American League, the first former player to be so elected and the fourth full-time chief executive in the league's history. When he replaced the retiring [[Will Harridge]], who became board chairman, Cronin moved the league's headquarters from [[Chicago]] to [[Boston]]. Cronin served as AL president until December 31, 1973, when he was succeeded by [[Lee MacPhail]].\n\nDuring Cronin's 15 years in office, the Junior Circuit [[expansion team|expanded]] from eight to 12 teams, adding the [[Los Angeles Angels]] and [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|expansion Washington Senators]] in {{baseball year|1961}}<ref>[https://sabr.org/research/mis-management-101-american-league-expansion-1961 McCue, Andy, and Thompson, Eric (2011), \"Mismanagement 101: The American League's Expansion of 1961.\" ''The National Pastime 2011,'' [[Society for American Baseball Research]]]</ref>  and the [[Kansas City Royals]] and [[Seattle Pilots]] in {{baseball year|1969}}.\n\nIt also endured four franchise shifts: the relocation of the original Senators club (owned by Cronin's brother-in-law and sister-in-law, [[Calvin Griffith]] and [[Thelma Griffith Haynes]]) to [[Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul]], creating the [[Minnesota Twins]] (1961); the shift of the [[Oakland Athletics|Athletics]] from [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]] to [[Oakland, California|Oakland]] ({{baseball year|1968}}); the transfer of the Pilots after only one season in [[Seattle]] to [[Milwaukee]] as the [[Milwaukee Brewers|Brewers]] ({{baseball year|1970}}); and the transplantation of the expansion Senators after 11 seasons in Washington, D.C., to [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth]] as the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] ({{baseball year|1972}}). The Angels also moved from Los Angeles to adjacent [[Orange County, California|Orange County]] in {{baseball year|1966}} and adopted a regional identity, in part because of the dominance of the [[National League]] [[Los Angeles Dodgers|Dodgers]], who were the Angels' landlords at [[Dodger Stadium|\"Chavez Ravine\" (Dodger Stadium)]] from 1962\u201365.  Of the four expansion teams that joined the league beginning in 1961, three abandoned their original host cities within a dozen years (the Pilots after only one season), and only one team\u2014the Royals\u2014remained in its original municipality. Two of the charter members of the old eight-team league, the [[Chicago White Sox]] and [[Cleveland Indians]], also suffered significant attendance woes and were targets of relocation efforts by other cities.\n\nIn addition, the AL found itself at a competitive disadvantage compared with the National League during Cronin's term. With strong teams in larger markets and a host of new stadiums, the NL outdrew the AL for 33 consecutive years (1956\u201388).<ref name=\"joeblows\">{{cite book|last1=Studenmund|first1=Dave|last2=Tamer|first2=Greg|title=The Hardball Times 2004 Baseball Annual|year=2004|publisher=The Hardball Times|isbn=|page=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0ry_K7X-iKIC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> In 1973, Cronin's final season as league president, the NL attracted 55 percent of total MLB attendance, 16.62 million vs. 13.38 million total fans, despite the opening of [[Royals Stadium]] in Kansas City and the American League's adoption of the [[designated hitter]] rule, which was designed to spark scoring and fan interest. While the National League held only an 8\u20137 edge in [[World Series]] play during the Cronin era, it dominated the [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game]], going 15\u20133\u20131 in the 19 games played from 1959\u201373.\n\nAfter the {{by|1968}} season, Cronin drew headlines when he fired AL [[umpire (baseball)|umpires]] [[Al Salerno]] and [[Bill Valentine]], ostensibly for poor performance; however, it later surfaced that the two officials were fired for attempting to organize an umpires' [[trade union|union]]. Neither man was reinstated (Valentine became a successful [[minor league baseball|minor league]] front-office executive), but the [[Major League Umpires Association]] was formed anyway, two years later.<ref>{{cite news|first=Mark|last=Armour|title=A Tale of Two Umpires: When Al Salerno and Bill Valentine Were Thrown Out of the Game|url=http://sabr.org/research/tale-two-umpires-when-al-salerno-and-bill-valentine-got-thrown-out-game|accessdate=July 14, 2017|agency=[[Society for American Baseball Research]]|publisher=sabr.org|date=2009}}</ref> However, in 1966, Cronin was hailed for [[racial integration|integrating]] MLB's umpiring staff with the promotion of veteran minor league arbiter [[Emmett Ashford]] to the American League.<ref>{{cite news|first=Mark|last=Armour|title=Emmett Ashford|url=https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/40af3222|accessdate=July 14, 2017|agency=[[Society for American Baseball Research]]|publisher=sabr.org|date=2007}}</ref>\n\n{{MLBBioRet\n|Image  = Red sox retired 4.png\n|Name   = Joe Cronin\n|Number = 4\n|Team   = Boston Red Sox\n|Year   = 1984\n|}}\n\n===Hall of Fame===\nJoe Cronin was inducted into the [[Baseball Hall of Fame]] (with [[Hank Greenberg]]) in 1956.\n\n==Career Statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! [[Games played|G]] !! [[At bat|AB]] !! [[Run (baseball)|R]] !! [[Hit (baseball)|H]] !! [[Double (baseball)|2B]] !! [[Triple (baseball)|3B]] !! [[Home run|HR]] !! [[Runs batted in|RBI]] !! [[Base on balls|BB]] !! [[Batting average (baseball)|AVG]] !! [[On-base percentage|OBP]] !! [[Slugging percentage|SLG]] !! [[Fielding percentage|FLD%]]\n|-\n| 2,124 || 7,579 || 1,233 || 2,285 || 515 || 118 || 170 || 1,424 || 1,059 || .301 || .390 || .468 || .953\n|}\n\n==Death==\nIn the last months of his life, Cronin struggled with cancer that had invaded his prostate and bones; he suffered a great deal of bone pain as a result.<ref>Armour, p. 330.</ref> Cronin came to [[Fenway Park]] for one of his last public appearances when his jersey number 4 was retired by the Red Sox on May 29, 1984. He died at the age of 77 on September 7, 1984, at his home in [[Osterville, Massachusetts]].<ref name=Morning>{{cite news|title=Joe Cronin, baseball legend, American League president|url=http://articles.mcall.com/1984-09-08/news/2428646_1_first-al-pennant-joe-cronin-great-man|accessdate=November 29, 2014|work=[[The Morning Call]]|date=September 8, 1984}}</ref> He is buried in St. Francis Xavier Cemetery in nearby Centerville.\n\n==Legacy==\nAt the number retirement ceremony shortly before Cronin's death, teammate [[Ted Williams]] commented on how much he respected Cronin as a father and a man. Cronin was also remembered as a [[clutch hitter]]. Manager [[Connie Mack]] once commented, \"With a man on third and one out, I'd rather have Cronin hitting for me than anybody I've ever seen, and that includes Cobb, Simmons and the rest of them.\"<ref name=NYT>{{cite news|title=Joe Cronin, an ex-executive and star player in baseball|url=http://www.thedeadballera.com/Obits/Obits_C/Cronin.Joe.Obit.html|accessdate=November 29, 2014|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 8, 1984}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, he was named to the [[Major League Baseball All-Century Team]].<ref name=ACT>{{cite web|title=The All-Century Team|url=http://www.mlb.com/mlb/history/mlb_history_moreinfo.jsp|publisher=[[MLB.com]]|accessdate=October 31, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Baseball}}\n* [[Boston Red Sox Hall of Fame]]\n* [[Bay Area Sports Hall of Fame]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career hits leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career doubles leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career triples leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career runs scored leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career runs batted in leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball annual doubles leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball annual triples leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball players to hit for the cycle]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball player-managers]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball managers by wins]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*Armour, Mark (2010). [https://books.google.com/books?id=nGZ9CyVWkmQC ''Joe Cronin: A Life in Baseball'']. [[University of Nebraska Press]]. {{ISBN|0803229968}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n{{bbhof|cronin-joe}}\n{{Baseballstats|mlb=|espn=|br=c/cronijo01|fangraphs=1002796|retro=C/Pcronj101}}\n{{Baseball-reference manager|cronijo01}}\n*{{findagrave}}\n^[https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/572b61e8 Joe Cronin] at SABR (Baseball BioProject)\n:<br>\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-ach|ach}}\n{{Succession box| before = [[Ski Melillo]]<br>[[Buddy Rosar]] | title = [[Hitting for the cycle]]| years = September 2, 1929<br>August 2, 1940 | after = [[Freddie Lindstrom]]<br>[[Joe Gordon]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{1956 Baseball HOF}}\n{{Baseball Hall of Fame members}}\n{{AL Presidents}}\n{{TwinsManagers}}\n{{Boston Red Sox retired numbers}}\n{{Boston Red Sox managers}}\n{{Boston Red Sox general managers}}\n{{Boston Red Sox Hall of Fame}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cronin, Joe}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1984 deaths]]\n[[Category:American League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:American League presidents]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from California]]\n[[Category:Boston Red Sox executives]]\n[[Category:Boston Red Sox managers]]\n[[Category:Boston Red Sox players]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Johnstown Johnnies players]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Blues (baseball) players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball general managers]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball player-managers]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball players with retired numbers]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball shortstops]]\n[[Category:National Baseball Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:New Haven Profs players]]\n[[Category:People from Osterville, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Pirates players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Washington Senators (1901\u201360) managers]]\n[[Category:Washington Senators (1901\u201360) players]]\n", "name_user": "98.200.14.137", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Cronin"}
{"title_page": "Marco Scutaro", "text_new": "{{short description|Venezuelan baseball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Marco Scutaro\n|image=Marco Scutaro 2012.jpg\n|image_size=250px\n|caption=Scutaro during the 2012 San Francisco Giants World Series Champions Homecoming Parade\n|position=[[Shortstop]] / [[Second baseman]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1975|10|30}}\n|birth_place=[[San Felipe, Yaracuy]], [[Venezuela]]\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=July 21\n|debutyear=2002\n|debutteam=New York Mets\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=July 24\n|finalyear=2014\n|finalteam=San Francisco Giants\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value=.277\n|stat2label=[[Home run]]s\n|stat2value=77\n|stat3label=[[Runs batted in]]\n|stat3value=509\n|teams=\n* [[New York Mets]] ({{mlby|2002}}\u2013{{mlby|2003}})\n* [[Oakland Athletics]] ({{mlby|2004}}\u2013{{mlby|2007}})\n* [[Toronto Blue Jays]] ({{mlby|2008}}\u2013{{mlby|2009}})\n* [[Boston Red Sox]] ({{mlby|2010}}\u2013{{mlby|2011}})\n* [[Colorado Rockies]] ({{mlby|2012}})\n* [[San Francisco Giants]] ({{mlby|2012}}\u2013{{mlby|2014}})\n|highlights=\n* [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[2013 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2013]])\n* [[World Series]] champion ({{wsy|2012}})\n* [[NLCS MVP]] ([[2012 NLCS|2012]])\n}}\n{{MedalTableTop}}\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[baseball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{VEN}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[World Baseball Classic]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | [[2009 World Baseball Classic|2009 Los Angeles]] | [[Venezuela national baseball team|Team]]}}\n{{MedalBottom}}\n<!--***DO NOT CHANGE** His full name is MARCOS (NOT MARCO) Scutaro***/-->'''Marcos Scutaro''', better known as '''Marco Scutaro''',<!--***DO NOT CHANGE** His full name is MARCOS (NOT MARCO) Scutaro***/--><ref name=\"MLB\"/> ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|k|u\u02d0|t|\u0259r|o\u028a}}<!-- Please correct this if it is wrong. (fixed for English pron., assuming stress is correct)-->; born October 30, 1975) is a [[Venezuela]]n former [[professional baseball]] [[infielder]]. He bats and throws right-handed. Scutaro made his MLB debut with the [[New York Mets]] in 2002. Since then, he has also played for the [[Oakland Athletics]], [[Toronto Blue Jays]], [[Boston Red Sox]], [[Colorado Rockies]] and [[San Francisco Giants]]. Scutaro was named the [[National League Championship Series Most Valuable Player Award|most valuable player]] of the [[2012 National League Championship Series]] while with the Giants.\n\nScutaro was one of the primary subjects of the 2005 documentary ''A Player to be Named Later''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gloria|first1=Justin|title=MLB News: Marco Scutaro Has Back Surgery, Baseball Career Still Up In The Air|url=http://au.ibtimes.com/mlb-news-marco-scutaro-has-back-surgery-baseball-career-still-air-1403336|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122025654/http://au.ibtimes.com/mlb-news-marco-scutaro-has-back-surgery-baseball-career-still-air-1403336|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 22, 2015|accessdate=January 22, 2015|work=International Business Times|date=December 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nScutaro was born in [[San Felipe, Yaracuy]], [[Venezuela]].<ref name=\"MLB\">{{cite web|title=Marco Scutaro|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player.jsp?player_id=340192|publisher=MLB|accessdate=October 23, 2012}}</ref> He is of Italian descent.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Edes|first1=Gordon|authorlink1=Gordon Edes|title=He'd take a ring over a starring role|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/boston/mlb/columns/story?columnist=edes_gordon&id=5018239|accessdate=January 22, 2015|publisher=ESPN.com|date=March 22, 2010}}</ref> He began playing baseball at age six.<ref name=\"Vizquel provided inspiration\">{{cite news|last=Kroichick|first=Ron|title=Vizquel provided inspiration for young Scutaro|url=http://www.sfgate.com/sports/kroichick/article/Vizquel-provided-inspiration-for-young-Scutaro-2550187.php|accessdate=October 23, 2012|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle|date=October 10, 2006}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Cleveland Indians===\nScutaro originally signed with the [[Cleveland Indians]] as an amateur free agent on July 26, 1994. As a teenager, Scutaro considered fellow Venezuelan [[Omar Vizquel]] his favorite player and would often watch Vizquel at spring training.<ref name=\"Vizquel provided inspiration\"/><ref name=\"Marco Scutaro gives SF Giants a lift\">{{cite news|last=Schulman|first=Henry|title=Marco Scutaro gives SF Giants a lift|url=http://www.sfgate.com/giants/article/Marco-Scutaro-gives-SF-Giants-a-lift-3818744.php|accessdate=October 23, 2012|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle|date=August 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Milwaukee Brewers===\nScutaro was traded by the Indians to the [[Milwaukee Brewers]] on August 30, 2000, as the \"player to be named later\" in a trade that had sent [[Kane Davis]], [[Paul Rigdon]] and [[Richie Sexson]] to the Brewers for [[Jason Bere]], [[Bob Wickman]] and [[Steve Woodard]] on July 28. Scutaro was in the 2005 documentary film [https://web.archive.org/web/20110210030452/http://aplayertobenamedlater.com/ \"A Player To Be Named Later\"] which followed various players from [[Indianapolis Indians]], the Triple-A affiliate of the Milwaukee Brewers, for one season. He was waived at the start of the 2002 season by the Brewers who needed to make room for [[Nelson Figueroa]] on its roster.<ref name=\"ginofalangi\">{{cite web|url=http://newyork.mets.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20020719&content_id=85683&vkey=news_nym&fext=.jsp&c_id=nym|author=Mulrenin, Patrick|title=Mets make roster moves\"|date=July 19, 2002|publisher=Newyork.mets.mlb.com|accessdate=December 5, 2012}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===New York Mets (2002\u20132003)===\nScutaro was claimed off waivers by the [[New York Mets]] on April 5, 2002. He batted .336 with 20 [[double (baseball)|double]]s, 7 [[home run]]s, 25 [[run batted in|runs batted in (RBI)]] and 39 [[run (baseball)|run]]s scored in 79 games with the Tides. He was also selected to the [[International League]] squad for the [[Triple-A All-Star Game]] that summer.<ref name=\"ginofalangi\"/>\n\nScutaro's first promotion to the majors came on July 19 when the Mets recalled him from the [[Norfolk Tides]] to replace the injured [[Joe McEwing]]. Scutaro introduced himself to Mets manager [[Bobby Valentine]] that afternoon while the latter was eating lunch at the hotel in [[Cincinnati]] where the team was staying. Valentine reciprocated the greeting without knowing who Scutaro was. After completing his meal, Valentine inquired about why Scutaro was lingering. \"I just got called up\", Scutaro responded.<ref name=\"ginofalangi\"/>\n\n[[File:Scutaroprint.jpg|thumb|180px|Scutaro batting for the Athletics in 2005]]\n===Oakland Athletics (2004\u20132007)===\nScutaro was again selected off waivers, this time by the [[Oakland Athletics]], on October 9, 2003.<ref>{{cite news|title=A's claim infielder Scutaro and outfielder Watson off waivers|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?id=1634533&src=mobile|accessdate=January 22, 2015|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ESPN.com|date=October 9, 2003}}</ref>\n\nScutaro landed a starting [[second baseman]] position after [[Mark Ellis (baseball)|Mark Ellis]] had a season-ending shoulder injury during 2004 [[spring training]].\n\nIn 2004, Scutaro reached career highs in [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]] (.273), [[runs batted in]] (43), [[Run (baseball)|runs]] (50), [[hit (baseball)|hits]] (124), [[Double (baseball)|doubles]] (32), [[at bat]]s (455) and [[games played]] (137). He played multiple positions, including second base, [[shortstop]], [[third baseman|third base]], and [[left fielder|left field]].\n\n===World Baseball Classic===\nBecause of his Italian heritage,<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/boston/mlb/columns/story?columnist=edes_gordon&id=5018239 Boston's Marco Scutaro would take a ring over a starring role] ''[[ESPN]]''</ref> Scutaro was given the option of playing for either [[Italian national baseball team|Italy]] or [[Venezuelan national baseball team|Venezuela]] in the [[2006 World Baseball Classic]]. He chose to play for Venezuela as a utility infielder. He again represented Venezuela in the [[2009 World Baseball Classic]] and [[2013 World Baseball Classic]]. Venezuela won the bronze medal in 2009, but in 2013  earned an early exit after a loss to Puerto Rico 6\u20133. However, Venezuela won against newcomers Spain to earn a direct qualification for the [[2017 World Baseball Classic]].\n\n===Toronto Blue Jays (2008\u20132009)===\n[[File:001U3148 Marco Scutaro.jpg|upright|thumb|Scutaro with the Blue Jays in 2009]]\nOn November 18, 2007, Scutaro was traded to the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] for minor league pitchers Kristian Bell and [[Graham Godfrey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=3117422 |title=ESPN \u2013 Oakland trades Scutaro to Toronto to free up playing time for Murphy \u2013 MLB |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=November 18, 2007 |accessdate=December 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\nScutaro was the Jays' third baseman for at least a month, after teammate [[Scott Rolen]] injured a finger, and then Scutaro returned to a starter's role after teammate [[David Eckstein]] injured his right hip flexor on May 6. Shortly after Eckstein's return, Eckstein and Blue Jays teammate [[Aaron Hill (baseball)|Aaron Hill]] collided trying to catch a fly ball. Hill suffered from concussion-like symptoms, and Scutaro filled in at second base.\n\nScutaro was the starting shortstop for the Blue Jays in 2009, and had his best season to date, achieving career highs in almost every offensive category: 12 home runs, 60 runs batted in, 35 doubles, 235 total bases, 162 hits, 100 runs, 14 [[stolen base]]s, and 90 [[base on balls|walks]] in 574 at-bats, all while playing slick defense all year.\n\n===Boston Red Sox (2010\u20132011)===\n[[File:Marco_Scutaro_2011.jpg|thumb|left|225px|Scutaro with the Red Sox in 2011]]\nOn December 3, 2009, Scutaro agreed to a two-year, $11&nbsp;million deal with the [[Boston Red Sox]]. The deal also included a third-year mutual option.<ref>[http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091203&content_id=7754398 Scutaro joins Red Sox with two-year pact] ''[[MLB.com]]''</ref> On April 12, 2010, Scutaro recorded the first hit in [[Target Field]] history on a single up the middle in the first inning off [[Minnesota Twins]] starter [[Carl Pavano]]. Soon after, Scutaro was caught stealing second base, making him the first out recorded at the Twins' new ballpark. In his first season with the team, Scutaro set a number of career highs, including games (150), at-bats (632), hits (174) and doubles (38) while suffering for much of the season with a right shoulder injury which forced him out of practice.<ref>[http://www.projo.com/redsox/content/Red_Sox_Scutaro_03-17-11_E1N21O2_v2.15cf445.html Red Sox Journal: Scutaro back to form] ''[[Providence Journal]]'', March 16, 2011</ref>\n\n===Colorado Rockies (2012)===\n[[File:Marco_Scutaro_19_Fielding.jpg|thumb|Scutaro fielding for the Rockies in 2012]]\nPrior to the 2012 season, the Red Sox and Scutaro agreed to exercise their mutual contract option. Then, on January 21, 2012, Scutaro was traded to the [[Colorado Rockies]] for [[pitcher]] [[Clayton Mortensen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120121&content_id=26417056&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb |title=Rockies fill infield hole with Marco Scutaro &#124; MLB.com: News |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date= |accessdate=December 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===San Francisco Giants (2012\u20132015)===\nOn July 27, 2012, Scutaro was traded, along with cash considerations, to the [[San Francisco Giants]] for infielder [[Charlie Culberson]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=401638 |title=GIANTS ACQUIRE SCUTARO FROM ROCKIES FOR CULBERSON |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=July 26, 2014 |date=July 28, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140726110229/http://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=401638 |archive-date=July 26, 2014 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In a game against the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] at [[Busch Stadium]] on August 8, 2012, Scutaro drove in a career high seven runs including a [[grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]].<ref>[http://scores.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=320808124. \"Marco Scutaro hits slam, drives in 7 as Giants clobber Cards\"] ''[[ESPN]]'', August 8, 2012.</ref> He hit .306 for the regular season, including .362 as a Giant, helping the Giants win the [[National League West]] title. He was awarded the [[NLCS MVP]] after tying the NLCS record with 14 hits and also batting .500 (14 for 28) with six runs scored and four runs batted in during [[2012 National League Championship Series|the seven game series against the Cardinals]].<ref>[http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20121022&content_id=39989528&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb. \"Record-setting effort nets Scutaro NLCS MVP\"] ''[[MLB.com]]'', October 22, 2012.</ref>  On October 28, in the tenth inning of Game 4 of the [[2012 World Series]], Scutaro drove in [[Ryan Theriot]] for the winning run, as the Giants swept the [[Detroit Tigers]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Les Carpenter |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/giants-sweep-tigers-for-world-series-title-on-marco-scutaro-s-winning-hit-.html |title=Giants sweep Tigers for World Series title on Marco Scutaro's winning hit \u2013 Yahoo! Sports |publisher=Sports.yahoo.com |date=October 29, 2012 |accessdate=December 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter the 2012 season, Scutaro and the Giants agreed to a 3-year, $20 million contract which became official on December 7, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=411208|title=Pagan and Scutaro finalize deals with Giants|work=TSN.ca|date=December 7, 2012|accessdate=December 8, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121209003005/http://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=411208|archive-date=December 9, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In 2013, Scutaro was the starting second baseman, with [[Tony Abreu]] and [[Nick Noonan]] as his main backups. In 81 games in the first half, Scutaro hit .316/.367/.400 with 2 HR, 22 RBI and 37 R, and he was named to the [[2013 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2013 MLB All-Star Game]]. Scutaro played his last game of 2013 on September 15, and was officially shut down on September 24.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/giants/ci_24170439/san-francisco-giants-shut-down-madison-bumgarner-marco |title=San Francisco Giants shut down Madison Bumgarner, Marco Scutaro for season |work=San Jose Mercury News |first=Alex |last=Pavlovic |date=September 24, 2013}}</ref> He underwent surgery on September 27 that inserted a pin in his left pinkie correcting his mallet finger, an injury he suffered on June 11 against the Pirates when he was hit by [[Tony Watson]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csnbayarea.com/giants/scutaro-have-surgery-friday-labels-giants-season-mess |title=Scutaro to have surgery Friday, labels Giants' season 'a mess' |work=CSN Bay Area |first=Andrew |last=Baggarly |date=September 24, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030131603/http://www.csnbayarea.com/giants/scutaro-have-surgery-friday-labels-giants-season-mess |archivedate=October 30, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 127 games in 2013, he hit .297/.357/.369 with 2 HR, 31 RBI and 57 R.\n\nScutaro started the 2014 season on the disabled list with back problems. He played in five games in July before his back issues forced him to return to the disabled list for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sanfrancisco.giants.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20140825&content_id=91383970&notebook_id=91405170&vkey=notebook_sf&c_id=sf |title=Scutaro won't return to Giants this season |first=Ryan |last=Hood |publisher=MLB.com |date=August 25, 2014 |accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref> On December 19, 2014, Scutaro underwent back surgery that some reports indicated could end his career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/giants-scutaro-has-back-surgery-may-end-career/|title=Giants\u2019 Scutaro has back surgery, may end career|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=December 22, 2014|accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/giants/article/SF-Giants-Marco-Scutaro-has-back-surgery-5974000.php|title=SF Giants\u2019 Marco Scutaro has back surgery; Sergio Romo discusses return|last=Schulman|first=Henry|work=sfgate.com|date=December 22, 2014|accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref> The Giants designated him for assignment on January 21, 2015, and he was removed from the 40-man roster.<ref>{{cite news|title=2B Marco Scutaro designated for assignment by Giants|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=mlb&id=12206112|accessdate=January 22, 2015|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ESPN.com|date=January 21, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Giants reportedly DFA veteran infielder Scutaro|url=http://m.giants.mlb.com/news/article/107037750/giants-reportedly-dfa-veteran-infielder-marco-scutaro|accessdate=January 22, 2015|publisher=MLB.com|date=January 21, 2015}}</ref>  On January 28, 2015, Scutaro was released by the Giants.<ref>{{cite news|title=Giants re-sign injured Marco Scutaro to end career with club|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=mlb&id=13102727|accessdate=June 17, 2015|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ESPN.com|date=June 17, 2015}}</ref> The Giants re-signed Scutaro to a major league contract on June 17 and placed him on the 60-day disabled list. He continued to rehabilitate his injury with the Giants, not with the intention of playing, but \"in hopes of maintaining a quality of life and be pain-free with his family,\" according to the Giants.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shea|first1=John|title=Marco Scutaro re-signs with Giants \u2014 not to play, though|url=http://www.sfgate.com/giants/article/Marco-Scutaro-re-signs-with-Giants-more-of-a-6333473.php|accessdate=June 17, 2015|work=San Francisco Chroncle|date=June 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Major League Baseball players from Venezuela]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n{{baseballstats|mlb=340192|espn=6966|br=s/scutama01|fangraphs=1555||brm=scutar001mar|retro=S/Pscutm001}}\n*[http://www.purapelota.com/lvbp/mostrar.php?id=scutmar001 Pura Pelota \u2013 Venezuelan Professional Baseball League statistics]\n\n{{NLCS MVP}}\n{{2012 San Francisco Giants}}\n{{Venezuela roster 2006 World Baseball Classic}}\n{{Venezuela roster 2009 World Baseball Classic}}\n{{Venezuela roster 2013 World Baseball Classic}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Baseball|Venezuela}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scutaro, Marco}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Akron Aeros players]]\n[[Category:Boston Red Sox players]]\n[[Category:Buffalo Bisons (minor league) players]]\n[[Category:Caribbean Series players]]\n[[Category:Caribes de Oriente players]]\n[[Category:Colorado Rockies players]]\n[[Category:Columbus RedStixx players]]\n[[Category:Indianapolis Indians players]]\n[[Category:Kinston Indians players]]\n[[Category:Leones del Caracas players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball players from Venezuela]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball second basemen]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball shortstops]]\n[[Category:National League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:National League Championship Series MVPs]]\n[[Category:New York Mets players]]\n[[Category:Norfolk Tides players]]\n[[Category:Oakland Athletics players]]\n[[Category:Pastora de los Llanos players]]\n[[Category:Pawtucket Red Sox players]]\n[[Category:People from Yaracuy]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Giants players]]\n[[Category:Toronto Blue Jays players]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan expatriate baseball players in Canada]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan expatriate baseball players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:2006 World Baseball Classic players]]\n[[Category:2009 World Baseball Classic players]]\n[[Category:2013 World Baseball Classic players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Venezuelan baseball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name=Marco Scutaro\n| image=Marco Scutaro 2012.jpg\n| image_size=250px\n| caption=Scutaro during the 2012 San Francisco Giants World Champions Homecoming Parade \n| position= [[Shortstop]] / [[Second baseman]]\n| bats=Right\n| throws=Right\n| birth_date={{Birth date and age|1975|10|30}}\n| birth_place=[[San Felipe, Yaracuy]], [[Venezuela]]\n|debutleague = MLB\n| debutdate=July 21\n| debutyear=2002\n| debutteam=New York Mets\n|finalleague = MLB\n| finaldate=July 24\n|finalyear=2014\n|finalteam=San Francisco Giants\n|statleague = MLB\n| stat1label=[[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n| stat1value=.277\n| stat2label=[[Home run]]s\n| stat2value=77\n| stat3label=[[Runs batted in]]\n| stat3value=509\n| teams=\n* [[New York Mets]] ({{mlby|2002}}\u2013{{mlby|2003}})\n* [[Oakland Athletics]] ({{mlby|2004}}\u2013{{mlby|2007}})\n* [[Toronto Blue Jays]] ({{mlby|2008}}\u2013{{mlby|2009}})\n* [[Boston Red Sox]] ({{mlby|2010}}\u2013{{mlby|2011}})\n* [[Colorado Rockies]] ({{mlby|2012}})\n* [[San Francisco Giants]] ({{mlby|2012}}\u2013{{mlby|2014}})\n| highlights=\n* [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[2013 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2013]])\n* [[World Series]] champion ({{wsy|2012}})\n* [[NLCS MVP]] ([[2012 NLCS|2012]])\n}}\n\n<!--***DO NOT CHANGE** His full name is MARCOS (NOT MARCO) Scutaro***/-->'''Marcos Scutaro''', better known as '''Marco Scutaro''',<!--***DO NOT CHANGE** His full name is MARCOS (NOT MARCO) Scutaro***/--><ref name=\"MLB\"/> ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|k|u\u02d0|t|\u0259r|o\u028a}}<!-- Please correct this if it is wrong. (fixed for English pron., assuming stress is correct)-->; born October 30, 1975) is a [[Venezuela]]n former [[professional baseball]] [[infielder]]. He bats and throws right-handed. Scutaro made his MLB debut with the [[New York Mets]] in 2002. Since then, he has also played for the [[Oakland Athletics]], [[Toronto Blue Jays]], [[Boston Red Sox]], [[Colorado Rockies]] and [[San Francisco Giants]]. Scutaro was named the [[National League Championship Series Most Valuable Player Award|most valuable player]] of the [[2012 National League Championship Series]] while with the Giants.\n\nScutaro was one of the primary subjects of the 2005 documentary ''A Player to be Named Later''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gloria|first1=Justin|title=MLB News: Marco Scutaro Has Back Surgery, Baseball Career Still Up In The Air|url=http://au.ibtimes.com/mlb-news-marco-scutaro-has-back-surgery-baseball-career-still-air-1403336|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122025654/http://au.ibtimes.com/mlb-news-marco-scutaro-has-back-surgery-baseball-career-still-air-1403336|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 22, 2015|accessdate=January 22, 2015|work=International Business Times|date=December 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nScutaro was born in [[San Felipe, Yaracuy]], [[Venezuela]].<ref name=\"MLB\">{{cite web|title=Marco Scutaro|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player.jsp?player_id=340192|publisher=MLB|accessdate=October 23, 2012}}</ref> He is of Italian descent.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Edes|first1=Gordon|authorlink1=Gordon Edes|title=He'd take a ring over a starring role|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/boston/mlb/columns/story?columnist=edes_gordon&id=5018239|accessdate=January 22, 2015|publisher=ESPN.com|date=March 22, 2010}}</ref> He began playing baseball at age six.<ref name=\"Vizquel provided inspiration\">{{cite news|last=Kroichick|first=Ron|title=Vizquel provided inspiration for young Scutaro|url=http://www.sfgate.com/sports/kroichick/article/Vizquel-provided-inspiration-for-young-Scutaro-2550187.php|accessdate=October 23, 2012|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle|date=October 10, 2006}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Cleveland Indians===\nScutaro originally signed with the [[Cleveland Indians]] as an amateur free agent on July 26, 1994. As a teenager, Scutaro considered fellow Venezuelan [[Omar Vizquel]] his favorite player and would often watch Vizquel at spring training.<ref name=\"Vizquel provided inspiration\"/><ref name=\"Marco Scutaro gives SF Giants a lift\">{{cite news|last=Schulman|first=Henry|title=Marco Scutaro gives SF Giants a lift|url=http://www.sfgate.com/giants/article/Marco-Scutaro-gives-SF-Giants-a-lift-3818744.php|accessdate=October 23, 2012|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle|date=August 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Milwaukee Brewers===\nScutaro was traded by the Indians to the [[Milwaukee Brewers]] on August 30, 2000, as the \"player to be named later\" in a trade that had sent [[Kane Davis]], [[Paul Rigdon]] and [[Richie Sexson]] to the Brewers for [[Jason Bere]], [[Bob Wickman]] and [[Steve Woodard]] on July 28. Scutaro was in the 2005 documentary film [https://web.archive.org/web/20110210030452/http://aplayertobenamedlater.com/ \"A Player To Be Named Later\"] which followed various players from [[Indianapolis Indians]], the Triple-A affiliate of the Milwaukee Brewers, for one season. He was waived at the start of the 2002 season by the Brewers who needed to make room for [[Nelson Figueroa]] on its roster.<ref name=\"ginofalangi\">{{cite web|url=http://newyork.mets.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20020719&content_id=85683&vkey=news_nym&fext=.jsp&c_id=nym|author=Mulrenin, Patrick|title=Mets make roster moves\"|date=July 19, 2002|publisher=Newyork.mets.mlb.com|accessdate=December 5, 2012}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===New York Mets (2002\u20132003)===\nScutaro was claimed off waivers by the [[New York Mets]] on April 5, 2002. He batted .336 with 20 [[double (baseball)|double]]s, 7 [[home run]]s, 25 [[run batted in|runs batted in (RBI)]] and 39 [[run (baseball)|run]]s scored in 79 games with the Tides. He was also selected to the [[International League]] squad for the [[Triple-A All-Star Game]] that summer.<ref name=\"ginofalangi\"/>\n\nScutaro's first promotion to the majors came on July 19 when the Mets recalled him from the [[Norfolk Tides]] to replace the injured [[Joe McEwing]]. Scutaro introduced himself to Mets manager [[Bobby Valentine]] that afternoon while the latter was eating lunch at the hotel in [[Cincinnati]] where the team was staying. Valentine reciprocated the greeting without knowing who Scutaro was. After completing his meal, Valentine inquired about why Scutaro was lingering. \"I just got called up\", Scutaro responded.<ref name=\"ginofalangi\"/>\n\n[[File:Scutaroprint.jpg|thumb|180px|Scutaro batting for the Athletics in 2005]]\n===Oakland Athletics (2004\u20132007)===\nScutaro was again selected off waivers, this time by the [[Oakland Athletics]], on October 9, 2003.<ref>{{cite news|title=A's claim infielder Scutaro and outfielder Watson off waivers|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?id=1634533&src=mobile|accessdate=January 22, 2015|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ESPN.com|date=October 9, 2003}}</ref>\n\nScutaro landed a starting [[second baseman]] position after [[Mark Ellis (baseball)|Mark Ellis]] had a season-ending shoulder injury during 2004 [[spring training]].\n\nIn 2004, Scutaro reached career highs in [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]] (.273), [[runs batted in]] (43), [[Run (baseball)|runs]] (50), [[hit (baseball)|hits]] (124), [[Double (baseball)|doubles]] (32), [[at bat]]s (455) and [[games played]] (137). He played multiple positions, including second base, [[shortstop]], [[third baseman|third base]], and [[left fielder|left field]].\n\n===World Baseball Classic===\nBecause of his Italian heritage,<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/boston/mlb/columns/story?columnist=edes_gordon&id=5018239 Boston's Marco Scutaro would take a ring over a starring role] ''[[ESPN]]''</ref> Scutaro was given the option of playing for either [[Italian national baseball team|Italy]] or [[Venezuelan national baseball team|Venezuela]] in the [[2006 World Baseball Classic]]. He chose to play for Venezuela as a utility infielder. He again represented Venezuela in the [[2009 World Baseball Classic]] and [[2013 World Baseball Classic]]. Venezuela won the bronze medal in 2009, but in 2013  earned an early exit after a loss to Puerto Rico 6\u20133. However, Venezuela won against newcomers Spain to earn a direct qualification for the [[2017 World Baseball Classic]].\n\n===Toronto Blue Jays (2008\u20132009)===\n[[File:001U3148 Marco Scutaro.jpg|upright|thumb|Scutaro with the Blue Jays in 2009]]\nOn November 18, 2007, Scutaro was traded to the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] for minor league pitchers Kristian Bell and [[Graham Godfrey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=3117422 |title=ESPN \u2013 Oakland trades Scutaro to Toronto to free up playing time for Murphy \u2013 MLB |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=November 18, 2007 |accessdate=December 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\nScutaro was the Jays' third baseman for at least a month, after teammate [[Scott Rolen]] injured a finger, and then Scutaro returned to a starter's role after teammate [[David Eckstein]] injured his right hip flexor on May 6. Shortly after Eckstein's return, Eckstein and Blue Jays teammate [[Aaron Hill (baseball)|Aaron Hill]] collided trying to catch a fly ball. Hill suffered from concussion-like symptoms, and Scutaro filled in at second base.\n\nScutaro was the starting shortstop for the Blue Jays in 2009, and had his best season to date, achieving career highs in almost every offensive category: 12 home runs, 60 runs batted in, 35 doubles, 235 total bases, 162 hits, 100 runs, 14 [[stolen base]]s, and 90 [[base on balls|walks]] in 574 at-bats, all while playing slick defense all year.\n\n===Boston Red Sox (2010\u20132011)===\n[[File:Marco_Scutaro_2011.jpg|thumb|left|225px|Scutaro with the Red Sox in 2011]]\nOn December 3, 2009, Scutaro agreed to a two-year, $11&nbsp;million deal with the [[Boston Red Sox]]. The deal also included a third-year mutual option.<ref>[http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091203&content_id=7754398 Scutaro joins Red Sox with two-year pact] ''[[MLB.com]]''</ref> On April 12, 2010, Scutaro recorded the first hit in [[Target Field]] history on a single up the middle in the first inning off [[Minnesota Twins]] starter [[Carl Pavano]]. Soon after, Scutaro was caught stealing second base, making him the first out recorded at the Twins' new ballpark. In his first season with the team, Scutaro set a number of career highs, including games (150), at-bats (632), hits (174) and doubles (38) while suffering for much of the season with a right shoulder injury which forced him out of practice.<ref>[http://www.projo.com/redsox/content/Red_Sox_Scutaro_03-17-11_E1N21O2_v2.15cf445.html Red Sox Journal: Scutaro back to form] ''[[Providence Journal]]'', March 16, 2011</ref>\n\n===Colorado Rockies (2012)===\n[[File:Marco_Scutaro_19_Fielding.jpg|thumb|Scutaro fielding for the Rockies in 2012]]\nPrior to the 2012 season, the Red Sox and Scutaro agreed to exercise their mutual contract option. Then, on January 21, 2012, Scutaro was traded to the [[Colorado Rockies]] for [[pitcher]] [[Clayton Mortensen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120121&content_id=26417056&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb |title=Rockies fill infield hole with Marco Scutaro &#124; MLB.com: News |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date= |accessdate=December 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===San Francisco Giants (2012\u20132015)===\nOn July 27, 2012, Scutaro was traded, along with cash considerations, to the [[San Francisco Giants]] for infielder [[Charlie Culberson]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=401638 |title=GIANTS ACQUIRE SCUTARO FROM ROCKIES FOR CULBERSON |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=July 26, 2014 |date=July 28, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140726110229/http://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=401638 |archive-date=July 26, 2014 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In a game against the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] at [[Busch Stadium]] on August 8, 2012, Scutaro drove in a career high seven runs including a [[grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]].<ref>[http://scores.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=320808124. \"Marco Scutaro hits slam, drives in 7 as Giants clobber Cards\"] ''[[ESPN]]'', August 8, 2012.</ref> He hit .306 for the regular season, including .362 as a Giant, helping the Giants win the [[National League West]] title. He was awarded the [[NLCS MVP]] after tying the NLCS record with 14 hits and also batting .500 (14 for 28) with six runs scored and four runs batted in during [[2012 National League Championship Series|the seven game series against the Cardinals]].<ref>[http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20121022&content_id=39989528&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb. \"Record-setting effort nets Scutaro NLCS MVP\"] ''[[MLB.com]]'', October 22, 2012.</ref>  On October 28, in the tenth inning of Game 4 of the [[2012 World Series]], Scutaro drove in [[Ryan Theriot]] for the winning run, as the Giants swept the [[Detroit Tigers]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Les Carpenter |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/giants-sweep-tigers-for-world-series-title-on-marco-scutaro-s-winning-hit-.html |title=Giants sweep Tigers for World Series title on Marco Scutaro's winning hit \u2013 Yahoo! Sports |publisher=Sports.yahoo.com |date=October 29, 2012 |accessdate=December 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter the 2012 season, Scutaro and the Giants agreed to a 3-year, $20 million contract which became official on December 7, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=411208|title=Pagan and Scutaro finalize deals with Giants|work=TSN.ca|date=December 7, 2012|accessdate=December 8, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121209003005/http://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=411208|archive-date=December 9, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In 2013, Scutaro was the starting second baseman, with [[Tony Abreu]] and [[Nick Noonan]] as his main backups. In 81 games in the first half, Scutaro hit .316/.367/.400 with 2 HR, 22 RBI and 37 R, and he was named to the [[2013 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2013 MLB All-Star Game]]. Scutaro played his last game of 2013 on September 15, and was officially shut down on September 24.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/giants/ci_24170439/san-francisco-giants-shut-down-madison-bumgarner-marco |title=San Francisco Giants shut down Madison Bumgarner, Marco Scutaro for season |work=San Jose Mercury News |first=Alex |last=Pavlovic |date=September 24, 2013}}</ref> He underwent surgery on September 27 that inserted a pin in his left pinkie correcting his mallet finger, an injury he suffered on June 11 against the Pirates when he was hit by [[Tony Watson]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csnbayarea.com/giants/scutaro-have-surgery-friday-labels-giants-season-mess |title=Scutaro to have surgery Friday, labels Giants' season 'a mess' |work=CSN Bay Area |first=Andrew |last=Baggarly |date=September 24, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030131603/http://www.csnbayarea.com/giants/scutaro-have-surgery-friday-labels-giants-season-mess |archivedate=October 30, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 127 games in 2013, he hit .297/.357/.369 with 2 HR, 31 RBI and 57 R.\n\nScutaro started the 2014 season on the disabled list with back problems. He played in five games in July before his back issues forced him to return to the disabled list for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sanfrancisco.giants.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20140825&content_id=91383970&notebook_id=91405170&vkey=notebook_sf&c_id=sf |title=Scutaro won't return to Giants this season |first=Ryan |last=Hood |publisher=MLB.com |date=August 25, 2014 |accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref> On December 19, 2014, Scutaro underwent back surgery that some reports indicated could end his career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/giants-scutaro-has-back-surgery-may-end-career/|title=Giants\u2019 Scutaro has back surgery, may end career|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=December 22, 2014|accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/giants/article/SF-Giants-Marco-Scutaro-has-back-surgery-5974000.php|title=SF Giants\u2019 Marco Scutaro has back surgery; Sergio Romo discusses return|last=Schulman|first=Henry|work=sfgate.com|date=December 22, 2014|accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref> The Giants designated him for assignment on January 21, 2015, and he was removed from the 40-man roster.<ref>{{cite news|title=2B Marco Scutaro designated for assignment by Giants|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=mlb&id=12206112|accessdate=January 22, 2015|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ESPN.com|date=January 21, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Giants reportedly DFA veteran infielder Scutaro|url=http://m.giants.mlb.com/news/article/107037750/giants-reportedly-dfa-veteran-infielder-marco-scutaro|accessdate=January 22, 2015|publisher=MLB.com|date=January 21, 2015}}</ref>  On January 28, 2015, Scutaro was released by the Giants.<ref>{{cite news|title=Giants re-sign injured Marco Scutaro to end career with club|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=mlb&id=13102727|accessdate=June 17, 2015|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ESPN.com|date=June 17, 2015}}</ref> The Giants re-signed Scutaro to a major league contract on June 17 and placed him on the 60-day disabled list. He continued to rehabilitate his injury with the Giants, not with the intention of playing, but \"in hopes of maintaining a quality of life and be pain-free with his family,\" according to the Giants.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shea|first1=John|title=Marco Scutaro re-signs with Giants \u2014 not to play, though|url=http://www.sfgate.com/giants/article/Marco-Scutaro-re-signs-with-Giants-more-of-a-6333473.php|accessdate=June 17, 2015|work=San Francisco Chroncle|date=June 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Major League Baseball players from Venezuela]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n{{baseballstats|mlb=340192|espn=6966|br=s/scutama01|fangraphs=1555||brm=scutar001mar|retro=S/Pscutm001}}\n*[http://www.purapelota.com/lvbp/mostrar.php?id=scutmar001 Pura Pelota \u2013 Venezuelan Professional Baseball League statistics]\n\n{{NLCS MVP}}\n{{2012 San Francisco Giants}}\n{{Venezuela roster 2006 World Baseball Classic}}\n{{Venezuela roster 2009 World Baseball Classic}}\n{{Venezuela roster 2013 World Baseball Classic}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Baseball|Venezuela}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scutaro, Marco}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Akron Aeros players]]\n[[Category:Boston Red Sox players]]\n[[Category:Buffalo Bisons (minor league) players]]\n[[Category:Caribbean Series players]]\n[[Category:Caribes de Oriente players]]\n[[Category:Colorado Rockies players]]\n[[Category:Columbus RedStixx players]]\n[[Category:Indianapolis Indians players]]\n[[Category:Kinston Indians players]]\n[[Category:Leones del Caracas players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball players from Venezuela]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball second basemen]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball shortstops]]\n[[Category:National League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:National League Championship Series MVPs]]\n[[Category:New York Mets players]]\n[[Category:Norfolk Tides players]]\n[[Category:Oakland Athletics players]]\n[[Category:Pastora de los Llanos players]]\n[[Category:Pawtucket Red Sox players]]\n[[Category:People from Yaracuy]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Giants players]]\n[[Category:Toronto Blue Jays players]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan expatriate baseball players in Canada]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan expatriate baseball players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:2006 World Baseball Classic players]]\n[[Category:2009 World Baseball Classic players]]\n[[Category:2013 World Baseball Classic players]]\n", "name_user": "98.200.14.137", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(fixed typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marco_Scutaro"}
{"title_page": "Spike Owen", "text_new": "{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Spike Owen\n|image=Spike Owen (28670705842) (cropped).jpg\n|caption=Owen with the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] in 2016\n|position=[[Shortstop]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1961|4|19}}\n|birth_place=[[Cleburne, Texas]]\n|bats=Switch\n|throws=Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=June 25\n|debutyear=1983\n|debutteam=Seattle Mariners\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=October 2\n|finalyear=1995\n|finalteam=California Angels\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value=.246\n|stat2label=[[Home run]]s\n|stat2value=46\n|stat3label=[[Runs batted in]]\n|stat3value=439\n|teams=\n*[[Seattle Mariners]] ({{mlby|1983}}\u2013{{mlby|1986}})\n*[[Boston Red Sox]] ({{mlby|1986}}\u2013{{mlby|1988}})\n*[[Montreal Expos]] ({{mlby|1989}}\u2013{{mlby|1992}})\n*[[New York Yankees]] ({{mlby|1993}})\n*[[California Angels]] ({{mlby|1994}}\u2013{{mlby|1995}})\n}}\n{{MedalTableTop}}\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[baseball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{USA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[World Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[1981 World Games|1981 Santa Clara]] | [[United States national baseball team|Team]]}}\n{{MedalBottom}}\n'''Spike Dee Owen''' (born April 19, 1961) is an American former [[shortstop]] in [[Major League Baseball]] who played for the [[Seattle Mariners]] (1983\u201386), [[Boston Red Sox]] (1986\u201388), [[Montreal Expos]] (1989\u201392), [[New York Yankees]] (1993) and [[California Angels]] (1994\u201395). He made his major league debut on June 25, 1983.\nIn his 13 seasons in the majors, he hit for a .246 [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]] with 46 [[home run]]s and 439 [[run batted in|RBI]]s in 1544 [[games played|games]].\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Player ===\n\nA [[switch-hitter]], he attended [[University of Texas at Austin|The University of Texas at Austin]] and was the All-Tournament Team shortstop in the [[1982 College World Series]]. He was drafted by the [[Seattle Mariners]] in the first round (the sixth overall pick) of the [[1982 Major League Baseball Draft|1982 amateur draft]].\n\nOn June 25, 1983 he went 1 for 4 against the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] in his major league debut with the Mariners.  His first hit came off [[Jim Gott]]. On July 13, 1983, he hit his first big league [[home run]] against [[Boston Red Sox]] pitcher [[Doug Bird]] at [[Fenway Park]].\n\nIn [[1986 in sports|1986]], he was named team captain of the Mariners.<ref>{{cite web|last=Street|first=Jim|title=Mailbag: What's lowdown on Lowe?|url=http://seattle.mariners.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070604&content_id=2005778&vkey=news_sea&fext=.jsp&c_id=sea|work=[[MLB.com]]|accessdate=August 29, 2010|date=June 4, 2007|archive-date=June 17, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110617062130/http://seattle.mariners.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070604&content_id=2005778&vkey=news_sea&fext=.jsp&c_id=sea}}</ref> On August 19, Owen and center fielder [[Dave Henderson]] were traded to the [[Boston Red Sox]] for [[Rey Qui\u00f1ones]], [[Mike Trujillo]], [[Mike Brown (pitcher)|Mike Brown]] and a player to be named later.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1986-08-18/sports/sp-18144_1_pennant-race|title=Red Sox Get Spike Owen From Mariners|date=August 18, 1986|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref> In his third game with the Red Sox, he tied a major league record with six [[run (baseball)|runs]] scored in a game. In the [[1986 American League Championship Series]], he hit .429 as the Red Sox, one scant strike away from elimination in Game 5, came back (starting with Henderson's go-ahead homer against closer [[Donnie Moore]]) and upended the [[California Angels]] 4 games to 3. In the [[1986 World Series]], he hit .300 in a Boston loss to the [[New York Mets]] 4 games to 3 after having the Mets down to their last strike twice in extra innings of Game 6.\n\nOn December 8, 1988, the [[Red Sox]] traded him to the [[Montreal Expos]] for pitcher [[John Dopson]] and shortstop [[Luis Rivera (infielder)|Lu\u00eds Rivera]].\n\nIn [[1990 in sports|1990]], he set a [[National League]] record with 63 consecutive [[error (baseball)|errorless]] games at shortstop. Despite hitting only .234, he showed some decent power with 24 [[double (baseball)|doubles]], 5 [[triple (baseball)|triples]] and 5 home runs among his 106 [[hit (baseball)|hits]]. Patience at the plate was the secret of his success with 70 [[base on balls|walks]] (12 intentional), for a respectable .333 [[on-base percentage]]. Walks are important for an eighth-place hitter in the NL because there is no [[designated hitter]], the usually weak-hitting [[pitcher]] bats ninth, and the top of the order starts the next inning if the pitcher makes the last out. Also, if the pitcher bats with less than two outs, he can make a productive out by bunting the runner(s) over.\n\nOwen's most productive season was [[1992 in sports|1992]], with career highs in average (.269), home runs (7), [[stolen base]]s (7) and [[slugging percentage]] (.381). In addition, he had a healthy .348 [[on-base percentage]] and hit well in the clutch at .319 in 91 [[at bat|at-bats]] with runners in scoring position. He also led the NL in [[fielding percentage]] twice. A hard-nosed competitor, he quickly established himself as a leader in the Montreal clubhouse and helped rookie [[Delino DeShields]] transition to [[second base]].\n\nAfter the 1992 season, Owen was supplanted as Montreal shortstop by the emergence of [[Wil Cordero]] and became a free agent. On December 4, 1992, he signed a three-year contract with the [[New York Yankees]], aspiring to anchor their infield and provide team leadership. However, in 1993, he led a horde of AL middle infielders in one category\u2014salary. Not surprisingly, the Yanks traded him after the 1993 season to the [[California Angels]] for a mere [[minor league baseball|minor leaguer]].\n\nIn [[1994 in sports|1994]], he hit a career-high .310 in 82 games for the Angels as an infield backup and eventually as a [[designated hitter|DH]].\n\nIn [[1996 in sports|1996]], he was demoted to the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]]' [[AAA (baseball)|Triple A]] affiliate, the [[Oklahoma City 89ers]], and in April, Owen announced his retirement.\n\n=== Coach ===\n\nOwen was a coach of the [[Round Rock Express]] from 2002 to 2006 (as a [[Houston Astros]] affiliate) and again from 2011 to 2014 (as a [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] affiliate).<ref name=\"round-rock\">{{cite web |title=Rangers Announce Express Field Staff |url=https://www.milb.com/round-rock/news/rangers-announce-express-field-staff/c-103161526 |website=MiLB.com |accessdate=June 17, 2019 |language=en |date=December 4, 2014}}</ref>  He was the manager of the [[High Desert Mavericks]], [[Class A-Advanced]] affiliate of the Texas Rangers in 2015,<ref name=\"round-rock\" /> where he guided the team to a 78-62 record and a second-half South Division title in the [[California League]].\n\nAfter the 2015 season, Owen was named to manage the [[Hickory Crawdads]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Aaron |last=Cox | url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20151203&content_id=158749052&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_t448 |title='Dads 2016 Coaching Staff Announced |website=[[MiLB.com]]|date=December 3, 2015 |accessdate=November 1, 2016}}</ref> a [[Class A (baseball)|Class A]] affiliate of the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]], however he was called up to the Rangers in February 2016 to serve as interim third base coach while third base coach [[Tony Beasley]] underwent chemotherapy treatment for cancer.<ref>{{cite web | agency=[[Associated Press]] | url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/14864997/spike-owen-texas-rangers-interim-third-base-coach-tony-beasley |title=Spike Owen is Rangers' interim 3B coach for Tony Beasley |website=[[ESPN.com]] |date=February 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Aaron |last=Cox | url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20160229&content_id=165744702&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_t448 |title=Mintz Replaces Owen as 'Dads Manager |website=[[MiLB.com]]|date=February 29, 2016 |accessdate=November 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOwen managed Hickory again in 2017. He managed the [[Down East Wood Ducks]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite news|title=Johnson promoted in Texas organization; Spike Owen to manage Woodies|url=http://wnct.com/2017/12/07/johnson-promoted-in-texas-organization-spike-owen-to-manage-woodies/|accessdate=December 21, 2017|work=[[WNCT-TV]]|date=December 7, 2017|first=Brian|last=Bailey}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Honeycutt|first1=Jordan|title=Spike Owen to manage Wood Ducks in 2018|url=http://www.kinston.com/sports/20171207/spike-owen-to-manage-wood-ducks-in-2018|accessdate=December 21, 2017|work=[[Kinston Free Press]]|date=December 7, 2017}}</ref> The Rangers did not retain Owen after the 2018 season.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Jeff |title=Finally, some good news for Rangers and their injured top prospects |url=https://www.star-telegram.com/sports/mlb/texas-rangers/article220509435.html |accessdate=January 8, 2019 |work=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]] |date=October 23, 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Sullivan |first1=T.R. |title=Rangers' Shiraz Rehman excited about new role |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/rangers-shiraz-rehman-excited-about-new-role/c-299550278 |accessdate=January 8, 2019 |work=[[MLB.com]] |date=October 23, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHis older brother, [[Dave Owen (baseball)|Dave]], played for the [[Chicago Cubs]] in 1984\u201385.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Baseball stats|br=o/owensp01|brm=owen--001spi}}\n* [http://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/player.php?p=owensp01 Baseball Almanac]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051214010211/http://www.baseballlibrary.com/baseballlibrary/ballplayers/O/Owen_Spike.stm Baseball Library]\n\n{{1982 MLB Draft}}\n{{Seattle Mariners first round draft picks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Owen, Spike}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American expatriate baseball players in Canada]]\n[[Category:Baseball coaches from Texas]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Texas]]\n[[Category:Boston Red Sox players]]\n[[Category:California Angels players]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 1981 World Games]]\n[[Category:Lake Elsinore Storm players]]\n[[Category:Lynn Sailors players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball shortstops]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball third base coaches]]\n[[Category:Minor league baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:Minor league baseball managers]]\n[[Category:Montreal Expos players]]\n[[Category:New York Yankees players]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma City 89ers players]]\n[[Category:People from Cleburne, Texas]]\n[[Category:Salt Lake City Gulls players]]\n[[Category:Seattle Mariners players]]\n[[Category:Texas Longhorns baseball players]]\n[[Category:Texas Rangers coaches]]\n[[Category:World Games gold medalists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Spike Owen\n|image=Spike Owen (28670705842) (cropped).jpg\n|caption=Owen with the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] in 2016\n|position=[[Shortstop]]\n|bats=Switch\n|throws=Right\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1961|4|19}}\n|birth_place=[[Cleburne, Texas]]\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=June 25\n|debutyear=1983\n|debutteam=Seattle Mariners\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=October 2\n|finalyear=1995\n|finalteam=California Angels\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value=.246\n|stat2label=[[Home run]]s\n|stat2value=46\n|stat3label=[[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n|stat3value=439\n|teams=\n*[[Seattle Mariners]] ({{mlby|1983}}\u2013{{mlby|1986}})\n*[[Boston Red Sox]] ({{mlby|1986}}\u2013{{mlby|1988}})\n*[[Montreal Expos]] ({{mlby|1989}}\u2013{{mlby|1992}})\n*[[New York Yankees]] ({{mlby|1993}})\n*[[California Angels]] ({{mlby|1994}}\u2013{{mlby|1995}})\n|medaltemplates=\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[baseball]] }}\n{{MedalCountry | the {{USA}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[World Games]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[1981 World Games|1981 Santa Clara]] | [[Baseball at the 1981 World Games|Team competition]] }}\n}}\n\n'''Spike Dee Owen''' (born April 19, 1961) is an American former [[shortstop]] in [[Major League Baseball]] who played for the [[Seattle Mariners]] (1983\u201386), [[Boston Red Sox]] (1986\u201388), [[Montreal Expos]] (1989\u201392), [[New York Yankees]] (1993) and [[California Angels]] (1994\u201395). He made his major league debut on June 25, 1983.\nIn his 13 seasons in the majors, he hit for a .246 [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]] with 46 [[home run]]s and 439 [[run batted in|RBI]]s in 1544 [[games played|games]].\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Player ===\n\nA [[switch-hitter]], he attended [[University of Texas at Austin|The University of Texas at Austin]] and was the All-Tournament Team shortstop in the [[1982 College World Series]]. He was drafted by the [[Seattle Mariners]] in the first round (the sixth overall pick) of the [[1982 Major League Baseball Draft|1982 amateur draft]].\n\nOn June 25, 1983 he went 1 for 4 against the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] in his major league debut with the Mariners.  His first hit came off [[Jim Gott]]. On July 13, 1983, he hit his first big league [[home run]] against [[Boston Red Sox]] pitcher [[Doug Bird]] at [[Fenway Park]].\n\nIn [[1986 in sports|1986]], he was named team captain of the Mariners.<ref>{{cite web|last=Street|first=Jim|title=Mailbag: What's lowdown on Lowe?|url=http://seattle.mariners.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070604&content_id=2005778&vkey=news_sea&fext=.jsp&c_id=sea|work=[[MLB.com]]|accessdate=August 29, 2010|date=June 4, 2007|archive-date=June 17, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110617062130/http://seattle.mariners.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070604&content_id=2005778&vkey=news_sea&fext=.jsp&c_id=sea}}</ref> On August 19, Owen and center fielder [[Dave Henderson]] were traded to the [[Boston Red Sox]] for [[Rey Qui\u00f1ones]], [[Mike Trujillo]], [[Mike Brown (pitcher)|Mike Brown]] and a player to be named later.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1986-08-18/sports/sp-18144_1_pennant-race|title=Red Sox Get Spike Owen From Mariners|date=August 18, 1986|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref> In his third game with the Red Sox, he tied a major league record with six [[run (baseball)|runs]] scored in a game. In the [[1986 American League Championship Series]], he hit .429 as the Red Sox, one scant strike away from elimination in Game 5, came back (starting with Henderson's go-ahead homer against closer [[Donnie Moore]]) and upended the [[California Angels]] 4 games to 3. In the [[1986 World Series]], he hit .300 in a Boston loss to the [[New York Mets]] 4 games to 3 after having the Mets down to their last strike twice in extra innings of Game 6.\n\nOn December 8, 1988, the [[Red Sox]] traded him to the [[Montreal Expos]] for pitcher [[John Dopson]] and shortstop [[Luis Rivera (infielder)|Lu\u00eds Rivera]].\n\nIn [[1990 in sports|1990]], he set a [[National League]] record with 63 consecutive [[error (baseball)|errorless]] games at shortstop. Despite hitting only .234, he showed some decent power with 24 [[double (baseball)|doubles]], 5 [[triple (baseball)|triples]] and 5 home runs among his 106 [[hit (baseball)|hits]]. Patience at the plate was the secret of his success with 70 [[base on balls|walks]] (12 intentional), for a respectable .333 [[on-base percentage]]. Walks are important for an eighth-place hitter in the NL because there is no [[designated hitter]], the usually weak-hitting [[pitcher]] bats ninth, and the top of the order starts the next inning if the pitcher makes the last out. Also, if the pitcher bats with less than two outs, he can make a productive out by bunting the runner(s) over.\n\nOwen's most productive season was [[1992 in sports|1992]], with career highs in average (.269), home runs (7), [[stolen base]]s (7) and [[slugging percentage]] (.381). In addition, he had a healthy .348 [[on-base percentage]] and hit well in the clutch at .319 in 91 [[at bat|at-bats]] with runners in scoring position. He also led the NL in [[fielding percentage]] twice. A hard-nosed competitor, he quickly established himself as a leader in the Montreal clubhouse and helped rookie [[Delino DeShields]] transition to [[second base]].\n\nAfter the 1992 season, Owen was supplanted as Montreal shortstop by the emergence of [[Wil Cordero]] and became a free agent. On December 4, 1992, he signed a three-year contract with the [[New York Yankees]], aspiring to anchor their infield and provide team leadership. However, in 1993, he led a horde of AL middle infielders in one category\u2014salary. Not surprisingly, the Yanks traded him after the 1993 season to the [[California Angels]] for a mere [[minor league baseball|minor leaguer]].\n\nIn [[1994 in sports|1994]], he hit a career-high .310 in 82 games for the Angels as an infield backup and eventually as a [[designated hitter|DH]].\n\nIn [[1996 in sports|1996]], he was demoted to the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]]' [[AAA (baseball)|Triple A]] affiliate, the [[Oklahoma City 89ers]], and in April, Owen announced his retirement.\n\n=== Coach ===\n\nOwen was a coach of the [[Round Rock Express]] from 2002 to 2006 (as a [[Houston Astros]] affiliate) and again from 2011 to 2014 (as a [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] affiliate).<ref name=\"round-rock\">{{cite web |title=Rangers Announce Express Field Staff |url=https://www.milb.com/round-rock/news/rangers-announce-express-field-staff/c-103161526 |website=MiLB.com |accessdate=June 17, 2019 |language=en |date=December 4, 2014}}</ref>  He was the manager of the [[High Desert Mavericks]], [[Class A-Advanced]] affiliate of the Texas Rangers in 2015,<ref name=\"round-rock\" /> where he guided the team to a 78-62 record and a second-half South Division title in the [[California League]].\n\nAfter the 2015 season, Owen was named to manage the [[Hickory Crawdads]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Aaron |last=Cox | url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20151203&content_id=158749052&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_t448 |title='Dads 2016 Coaching Staff Announced |website=[[MiLB.com]]|date=December 3, 2015 |accessdate=November 1, 2016}}</ref> a [[Class A (baseball)|Class A]] affiliate of the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]], however he was called up to the Rangers in February 2016 to serve as interim third base coach while third base coach [[Tony Beasley]] underwent chemotherapy treatment for cancer.<ref>{{cite web | agency=[[Associated Press]] | url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/14864997/spike-owen-texas-rangers-interim-third-base-coach-tony-beasley |title=Spike Owen is Rangers' interim 3B coach for Tony Beasley |website=[[ESPN.com]] |date=February 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Aaron |last=Cox | url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20160229&content_id=165744702&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_t448 |title=Mintz Replaces Owen as 'Dads Manager |website=[[MiLB.com]]|date=February 29, 2016 |accessdate=November 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOwen managed Hickory again in 2017. He managed the [[Down East Wood Ducks]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite news|title=Johnson promoted in Texas organization; Spike Owen to manage Woodies|url=http://wnct.com/2017/12/07/johnson-promoted-in-texas-organization-spike-owen-to-manage-woodies/|accessdate=December 21, 2017|work=[[WNCT-TV]]|date=December 7, 2017|first=Brian|last=Bailey}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Honeycutt|first1=Jordan|title=Spike Owen to manage Wood Ducks in 2018|url=http://www.kinston.com/sports/20171207/spike-owen-to-manage-wood-ducks-in-2018|accessdate=December 21, 2017|work=[[Kinston Free Press]]|date=December 7, 2017}}</ref> The Rangers did not retain Owen after the 2018 season.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Jeff |title=Finally, some good news for Rangers and their injured top prospects |url=https://www.star-telegram.com/sports/mlb/texas-rangers/article220509435.html |accessdate=January 8, 2019 |work=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]] |date=October 23, 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Sullivan |first1=T.R. |title=Rangers' Shiraz Rehman excited about new role |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/rangers-shiraz-rehman-excited-about-new-role/c-299550278 |accessdate=January 8, 2019 |work=[[MLB.com]] |date=October 23, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHis older brother, [[Dave Owen (baseball)|Dave]], played for the [[Chicago Cubs]] in 1984\u201385.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Baseball stats|br=o/owensp01|brm=owen--001spi}}\n* [http://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/player.php?p=owensp01 Baseball Almanac]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051214010211/http://www.baseballlibrary.com/baseballlibrary/ballplayers/O/Owen_Spike.stm Baseball Library]\n\n{{1982 MLB Draft}}\n{{Seattle Mariners first round draft picks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Owen, Spike}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American expatriate baseball players in Canada]]\n[[Category:Baseball coaches from Texas]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Texas]]\n[[Category:Boston Red Sox players]]\n[[Category:California Angels players]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 1981 World Games]]\n[[Category:Lake Elsinore Storm players]]\n[[Category:Lynn Sailors players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball shortstops]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball third base coaches]]\n[[Category:Minor league baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:Minor league baseball managers]]\n[[Category:Montreal Expos players]]\n[[Category:New York Yankees players]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma City 89ers players]]\n[[Category:People from Cleburne, Texas]]\n[[Category:Salt Lake City Gulls players]]\n[[Category:Seattle Mariners players]]\n[[Category:Texas Longhorns baseball players]]\n[[Category:Texas Rangers coaches]]\n[[Category:World Games gold medalists]]\n", "name_user": "98.200.14.137", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "",