{"title_page": "Abdel Aziz El Mubarak", "text_new": "{{short description|Sudanese musician}}\n{{sources|date=April 2010}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name            = Abdel Aziz El Mubarak\n|image             =\n|background      = solo_singer\n|birth_name      =\n|alias           =\n|birth_date          = 1951\n|birth_place         = [[Wad Madani]], [[Sudan]]\n|death_date           = {{Death date and given age|2020|2|9|69|df=y}}\n|origin          = \n|instrument      = [[Oud]], Orchestra\n|genre           = [[Music of Sudan]], [[Arabic]]\n|occupation      = Singer\n|years_active    = 1985\u20132020\n|label           = [[Globe Style]], [[World Circuit (record label)|World Circuit]]\n|associated_acts =\n|website             =\n}}\n\n'''Abdel Aziz El Mubarak''' ({{lang-ar|'''\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0632\u064a\u0632 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0628\u0627\u0631\u0643'''}};  1951 \u2013 9 February 2020) was a Sudanese singer, born in [[Wad Madani]]. He was known for leading a large band whose music was based on traditional [[Arab music]] but was also influenced by [[reggae]] and American [[rhythm and blues]]. In addition to releasing many [[compact audio cassette|cassette]] recordings in Sudan and playing many weddings and other gigs in Sudan, he and his band also recorded several [[compact discs|CDs]] for the European and American market and toured internationally. He also performed solo, accompanying himself on the [[oud]].<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p73632|pure_url=yes}}|title=Biography: Abdel Aziz El Mubarak|last=Jackson|first=Leon|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=4 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n;Albums\n* 1986:  ''Songs From The City'' (World Circuit)\n* 1987:  ''Tahrimni Minnak'' (GlobeStyle Records)\n* 1985:  ''Straight From The Heart'' (World Circuit)\n\n;Contributing artist\n* 2013: ''[[The Rough Guide to the Music of North Africa]]'' ([[World Music Network]])\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mubarak, Abdel Aziz El}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Oud players]]\n[[Category:Sudanese music]]\n[[Category:Sudanese singers]]\n[[Category:World Circuit (record label) artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n[[Category:People from Al Jazirah (state)]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pneumonia]]\n\n{{arabic-music-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Sudanese musician}}\n{{sources|date=April 2010}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name            = Abdel Aziz El Mubarak\n|image             =\n|background      = solo_singer\n|birth_name      =\n|alias           =\n|birth_date          = 1951\n|birth_place         = [[Wad Madani]], [[Sudan]]\n|death_date           = {{Death date and given age|2020|2|9|69|df=y}}\n|origin          = \n|instrument      = [[Oud]], Orchestra\n|genre           = [[Music of Sudan]], [[Arabic]]\n|occupation      = Singer\n|years_active    = 1985\u20132020\n|label           = [[Globe Style]], [[World Circuit (record label)|World Circuit]]\n|associated_acts =\n|website             =\n}}\n\n'''Abdel Aziz El Mubarak''' ({{lang-ar|'''\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0632\u064a\u0632 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0628\u0627\u0631\u0643'''}};  1951 \u2013 9 February 2020) was a Sudanese singer, born in [[Wad Madani]]. He was known for leading a large band whose music was based on traditional [[Arab music]] but was also influenced by [[reggae]] and American [[rhythm and blues]]. In addition to releasing many [[compact audio cassette|cassette]] recordings in Sudan and playing many weddings and other gigs in Sudan, he and his band also recorded several [[compact discs|CDs]] for the European and American market and toured internationally. He also performed solo, accompanying himself on the [[oud]].<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p73632|pure_url=yes}}|title=Biography: Abdel Aziz El Mubarak